# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: awq-quantization
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:awq-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] The **bfloat16** (**brain floating point**) floating-point format is a computer number format occupying 16 bits in computer memory; it represents a wide dynamic range of numeric values by using a floating radix point.
[src:awq-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] This format is a shortened (16-bit) version of the 32-bit IEEE 754 single-precision floating-point format (binary32) with the intent of accelerating machine learning and near-sensor computing.
[src:awq-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] It preserves the approximate dynamic range of 32-bit floating-point numbers by retaining 8 exponent bits, but supports only an 8-bit precision rather than the 24-bit significand of the binary32 format.
[src:awq-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] More so than single-precision 32-bit floating-point numbers, bfloat16 numbers are unsuitable for integer calculations, but this is not their intended use.
[src:awq-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] Bfloat16 is used to reduce the storage requirements and increase the calculation speed of machine learning algorithms.
[src:awq-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] The bfloat16 format was developed by Google Brain, an artificial intelligence research group at Google, for use in its TPU v2, released in 2017.
[src:awq-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] Many libraries support bfloat16, such as CUDA, Intel oneAPI Math Kernel Library, AMD ROCm, AMD Optimizing CPU Libraries, PyTorch, and TensorFlow.
[src:awq-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] On these platforms, bfloat16 may also be used in mixed-precision arithmetic, where bfloat16 numbers may be operated on and expanded to wider data types.
[src:awq-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] Preserving the exponent bits maintains the 32-bit float's range of ≈ 10−38 to ≈ 3 × 1038.
[src:awq-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] The bfloat16 binary floating-point exponent is encoded using an offset-binary representation, with the zero offset being 127; also known as exponent bias in the IEEE 754 standard.
[src:awq-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] Thus, in order to get the true exponent as defined by the offset-binary representation, the offset of 127 has to be subtracted from the value of the exponent field.
[src:awq-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] The minimum and maximum values of the exponent field (00H and FFH) are interpreted specially, like in the IEEE 754 standard formats.
[src:awq-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] The most common use case is the conversion between IEEE 754 binary32 and bfloat16.
[src:awq-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] The following section describes the conversion process and its rounding scheme in the conversion.
[src:awq-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] Note that there are other possible scenarios of format conversions to or from bfloat16.
[src:awq-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] Just as in IEEE 754, positive and negative infinity are represented with their corresponding sign bits, all 8 exponent bits set (FFhex) and all significand bits zero.
[src:awq-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] Just as in IEEE 754, NaN values are represented with either sign bit, all 8 exponent bits set (FFhex) and not all significand bits zero.
[src:awq-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] where at least one of *k, l, m, n, o, p,* or *q* is 1.
[src:awq-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] As with IEEE 754, NaN values can be quiet or signaling, although there are no known uses of signaling bfloat16 NaNs.
[src:awq-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] Bfloat16 is designed to maintain the number range from the 32-bit IEEE 754 single-precision floating-point format (binary32), while reducing the precision from 24 bits to 8 bits.
[src:awq-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] This means that the precision is between two and three decimal digits, and bfloat16 can represent finite values up to about 3.4 × 1038.
[src:awq-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] These examples are given in bit *representation*, in hexadecimal and binary, of the floating-point value.
[src:awq-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] This includes the sign, (biased) exponent, and significand.
[src:awq-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] The maximum positive finite value of a normal bfloat16 number is 3.38953139 × 1038, slightly below (224 − 1) × 2−23 × 2127 = 3.402823466 × 1038, the max finite positive value representable in single precision.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] In computing, **floating-point arithmetic** (**FP**) is arithmetic on subsets of real numbers formed by a *significand* (a signed sequence of a fixed number of digits in some base) multiplied by an integer power of that base.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Numbers of this form are called **floating-point numbers**.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The nearest floating-point number with only five digits is 12.346.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] And 1/3 = 0.3333… is not a floating-point number in base ten with any finite number of digits.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] In practice, most floating-point systems use base two, though base ten (decimal floating point) is also common.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Floating-point arithmetic operations, such as addition and division, approximate the corresponding real number arithmetic operations by rounding any result that is not a floating-point number itself to a nearby floating-point number.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] For example, in a floating-point arithmetic with five base-ten digits, the sum 12.345 + 1.0001 = 13.3451 might be rounded to 13.345.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The term *floating point* refers to the fact that the number's radix point can "float" anywhere to the left, right, or between the significant digits of the number.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] This position is indicated by the exponent, so floating point can be considered a form of scientific notation.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] A floating-point system can be used to represent, with a fixed number of digits, numbers of very different orders of magnitude — such as the number of meters between galaxies or between protons in an atom.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] For this reason, floating-point arithmetic is often used to allow very small and very large real numbers that require fast processing times.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The result of this dynamic range is that the numbers that can be represented are not uniformly spaced; the difference between two consecutive representable numbers varies with their exponent.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Over the years, a variety of floating-point representations have been used in computers.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] In 1985, the IEEE 754 Standard for Floating-Point Arithmetic was established, and since the 1990s, the most commonly encountered representations are those defined by the IEEE.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The speed of floating-point operations, commonly measured in terms of FLOPS, is an important characteristic of a computer system, especially for applications that involve intensive mathematical calculations.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Floating-point numbers can be computed using software implementations (softfloat) or hardware implementations (hardfloat).
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Floating-point units (FPUs, colloquially math coprocessors) are specially designed to carry out operations on floating-point numbers and are part of most computer systems.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] When FPUs are not available, software implementations can be used instead.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] A number representation specifies some way of encoding a number, usually as a string of digits.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] There are several mechanisms by which strings of digits can represent numbers.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] In standard mathematical notation, the digit string can be of any length, and the location of the radix point is indicated by placing an explicit "point" character (dot or comma) there.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] If the radix point is not specified, then the string implicitly represents an integer and the unstated radix point would be off the right-hand end of the string, next to the least significant digit.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] In fixed-point systems, a position in the string is specified for the radix point.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] So a fixed-point scheme might use a string of 8 decimal digits with the decimal point in the middle, whereby "00012345" would represent 0001.2345.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] In scientific notation, the given number is scaled by a power of 10, so that it lies within a specific range—typically between 1 and 10, with the radix point appearing immediately after the first digit.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] As a power of ten, the scaling factor is then indicated separately at the end of the number.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] For example, the orbital period of Jupiter's moon Io is 152,853.5047 seconds, a value that would be represented in standard-form scientific notation as 1.528535047×105 seconds.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Floating-point representation is similar in concept to scientific notation.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Using base-10 (the familiar decimal notation) as an example, the number 152,853.5047, which has ten decimal digits of precision, is represented as the significand 1528535047 together with 5 as the exponent.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] To determine the actual value, a decimal point is placed after the first digit of the significand and the result is multiplied by 105 to give 1.528535047×105, or 152,853.5047.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] In storing such a number, the base (10) need not be stored, since it will be the same for the entire range of supported numbers, and can thus be inferred.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] where s is the significand (ignoring any implied decimal point), p is the precision (the number of digits in the significand), b is the base (in our example, this is the number *ten*), and e is the exponent.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] A floating-point number is a rational number, because it can be represented as one integer divided by another; for example 1.45×103 is (145/100)×1000 or 145,000/100.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The base determines the fractions that can be represented; for instance, 1/5 cannot be represented exactly as a floating-point number using a binary base, but 1/5 can be represented exactly using a decimal base (0.2, or 2×10−1).
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The occasions on which infinite expansions occur depend on the base and its prime factors.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The way in which the significand (including its sign) and exponent are stored in a computer is implementation-dependent.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The common IEEE formats are described in detail later and elsewhere, but as an example, in the binary single-precision (32-bit) floating-point representation, $p=24$ , and so the significand is a string of 24 bits.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] In this binary expansion, let us denote the positions from 0 (leftmost bit, or most significant bit) to 32 (rightmost bit).
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The 24-bit significand will stop at position 23, shown as the underlined bit 0 above.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The next bit, at position 24, is called the *round bit* or *rounding bit*.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] It is used to round the 33-bit approximation to the nearest 24-bit number (there are specific rules for halfway values, which is not the case here).
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] When this is stored in memory using the IEEE 754 encoding, this becomes the significand s.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The significand is assumed to have a binary point to the right of the leftmost bit.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] where p is the precision (24 in this example), n is the position of the bit of the significand from the left (starting at 0 and finishing at 23 here) and e is the exponent (1 in this example).
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] It can be required that the most significant digit of the significand of a non-zero number be non-zero (except when the corresponding exponent would be smaller than the minimum one).
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] For binary formats (which uses only the digits 0 and 1), this non-zero digit is necessarily 1.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Therefore, it does not need to be represented in memory, allowing the format to have one more bit of precision.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] This rule is variously called the *leading bit convention*, the *implicit bit convention*, the *hidden bit convention*, or the *assumed bit convention*.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The floating-point representation is by far the most common way of representing in computers an approximation to real numbers.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] In 1914, the Spanish engineer Leonardo Torres Quevedo published *Essays on Automatics*, where he designed a special-purpose electromechanical calculator based on Charles Babbage's analytical engine and described a way to store floating-point numbers in a consistent manner.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] He stated that numbers will be stored in exponential format as $n\times 10^{m}$ , and offered three rules by which consistent manipulation of floating-point numbers by machines could be implemented.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] In 1938, Konrad Zuse of Berlin completed the Z1, the first binary, programmable mechanical computer; it uses a 24-bit binary floating-point number representation with a 7-bit signed exponent, a 17-bit significand (including one implicit bit), and a sign bit.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The more reliable relay-based Z3, completed in 1941, has representations for both positive and negative infinities; in particular, it implements defined operations with infinity, such as division by infinity, where $1/\infty =0$ , and it stops on undefined operations, such as $0\times \infty$ .
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Zuse also proposed, but did not complete, carefully rounded floating-point arithmetic that includes $\pm \infty$ and NaN representations, anticipating features of the IEEE Standard by four decades.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] In contrast, von Neumann recommended against floating-point numbers for the 1951 IAS machine, arguing that fixed-point arithmetic is preferable.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The first *commercial* computer with floating-point hardware was Zuse's Z4 computer, designed in 1942–1945.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] In 1946, Bell Laboratories introduced the Model V, which implemented decimal floating-point numbers.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The Pilot ACE has binary floating-point arithmetic, and it became operational in 1950 at National Physical Laboratory, UK.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Thirty-three were later sold commercially as the English Electric DEUCE.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The arithmetic is actually implemented in software, but with a one megahertz clock rate, the speed of floating-point and fixed-point operations in this machine were initially faster than those of many competing computers.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The mass-produced IBM 704 followed in 1954; it introduced the use of a biased exponent.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] For many decades after that, floating-point hardware was typically an optional feature, and computers that had it were said to be "scientific computers", or to have "scientific computation" (SC) capability (see also Extensions for Scientific Computation (XSC)).
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] It was not until the launch of the Intel i486 in 1989 that *general-purpose* personal computers had floating-point capability in hardware as a standard feature.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The IBM 7094, also introduced in 1962, supported single-precision and double-precision representations, but with no relation to the UNIVAC's representations.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Indeed, in 1964, IBM introduced hexadecimal floating-point representations in its System/360 mainframes; these same representations are still available for use in modern z/Architecture systems.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] In 1998, IBM implemented IEEE-compatible binary floating-point arithmetic in its mainframes; in 2005, IBM also added IEEE-compatible decimal floating-point arithmetic.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Initially, computers used many different representations for floating-point numbers.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Floating-point compatibility across multiple computing systems was in desperate need of standardization by the early 1980s, leading to the creation of the IEEE 754 standard once the 32-bit (or 64-bit) word had become commonplace.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] This standard was significantly based on a proposal from Intel, which was designing the i8087 numerical coprocessor; Motorola, which was designing the 68000 around the same time, gave significant input as well.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] In 1989, mathematician and computer scientist William Kahan was honored with the Turing Award for being the primary architect behind this proposal; he was aided by his student Jerome Coonen and a visiting professor, Harold Stone.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] However, the behavior may not be the same as a rounding to the destination format due to a possible wider exponent range of the extended format.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] A floating-point number consists of two fixed-point components, whose range depends exclusively on the number of bits or digits in their representation.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Whereas components linearly depend on their range, the floating-point range linearly depends on the significand range and exponentially on the range of exponent component, which attaches outstandingly wider range to the number.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] On a typical computer system, a *double-precision* (64-bit) binary floating-point number has a coefficient of 53 bits (including 1 implied bit), an exponent of 11 bits, and 1 sign bit.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Since 210 = 1024, the complete range of the positive normal floating-point numbers in this format is from 2−1022 ≈ 2 × 10−308 to approximately 21024 ≈ 2 × 10308.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] which has a 1 as the leading digit and 0 for the remaining digits of the significand, and the smallest possible value for the exponent.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] which has *B* − 1 as the value for each digit of the significand and the largest possible value for the exponent.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] In addition, there are representable values strictly between −UFL and UFL.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Namely, positive and negative zeros, as well as subnormal numbers.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The IEEE standardized the computer representation for binary floating-point numbers in IEEE 754 (a.k.a.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] This first standard is followed by almost all modern machines.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] IBM mainframes support IBM's own hexadecimal floating point format and IEEE 754-2008 decimal floating point in addition to the IEEE 754 binary format.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The Cray T90 series had an IEEE version, but the SV1 still uses Cray floating-point format.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The standard provides for many closely related formats, differing in only a few details.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Five of these formats are called *basic formats*, and others are termed *extended precision formats* and *extendable precision format*.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Increasing the precision of the floating-point representation generally reduces the amount of accumulated round-off error caused by intermediate calculations.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Any integer with absolute value less than 224 can be exactly represented in the single-precision format, and any integer with absolute value less than 253 can be exactly represented in the double-precision format.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Furthermore, a wide range of powers of 2 times such a number can be represented.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] These properties are sometimes used for purely integer data, to get 53-bit integers on platforms that have double-precision floats but only 32-bit integers.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The standard specifies some special values, and their representation: positive infinity (+∞), negative infinity (−∞), a negative zero (−0) distinct from ordinary ("positive") zero, and "not a number" values (NaNs).
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Comparison of floating-point numbers, as defined by the IEEE standard, is a bit different from usual integer comparison.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Negative and positive zero compare equal, and every NaN compares unequal to every value, including itself.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] All finite floating-point numbers are strictly smaller than +∞ and strictly greater than −∞, and they are ordered in the same way as their values (in the set of real numbers).
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Floating-point numbers are typically packed into a computer datum as the sign bit, the exponent field, and a field for the significand, from left to right.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] While the exponent can be positive or negative, in binary formats it is stored as an unsigned number that has a fixed "bias" added to it.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Values of all 0s in this field are reserved for the zeros and subnormal numbers; values of all 1s are reserved for the infinities and NaNs.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Normal numbers exclude subnormal values, zeros, infinities, and NaNs.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] In the IEEE binary interchange formats the leading bit of a normalized significand is not actually stored in the computer datum, since it is always 1.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] It is called the "hidden" or "implicit" bit.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Because of this, the single-precision format actually has a significand with 24 bits of precision, the double-precision format has 53, quad has 113, and octuple has 237.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] and the 64-bit ("double") layout is similar.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] In addition to the widely used IEEE 754 standard formats, other floating-point formats are used, or have been used, in certain domain-specific areas.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] By their nature, all numbers expressed in floating-point format are rational numbers with a terminating expansion in the relevant base (for example, a terminating decimal expansion in base-10, or a terminating binary expansion in base-2).
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Irrational numbers, such as π or ${\textstyle {\sqrt {2}}}$ , or non-terminating rational numbers, must be approximated.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The number of digits (or bits) of precision also limits the set of rational numbers that can be represented exactly.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] When a number is represented in some format (such as a character string) which is not a native floating-point representation supported in a computer implementation, then it will require a conversion before it can be used in that implementation.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] If the number can be represented exactly in the floating-point format then the conversion is exact.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] If there is not an exact representation then the conversion requires a choice of which floating-point number to use to represent the original value.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The representation chosen will have a different value from the original, and the value thus adjusted is called the *rounded value*.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Whether or not a rational number has a terminating expansion depends on the base.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] For example, in base-10 the number 1/2 has a terminating expansion (0.5) while the number 1/3 does not (0.333...).
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] In base-2 only rationals with denominators that are powers of 2 (such as 1/2 or 3/16) are terminating.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Any rational with a denominator that has a prime factor other than 2 will have an infinite binary expansion.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] This means that numbers that appear to be short and exact when written in decimal format may need to be approximated when converted to binary floating-point.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] where, as previously, *s* is the significand and *e* is the exponent.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] when approximated by rounding to a precision of 24 bits.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The result of rounding differs from the true value by about 0.03 parts per million, and matches the decimal representation of π in the first 7 digits.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The difference is the discretization error and is limited by the machine epsilon.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The arithmetical difference between two consecutive representable floating-point numbers which have the same exponent is called a unit in the last place (ULP).
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] For example, if there is no representable number lying between the representable numbers 1.45A70C2216 and 1.45A70C2416, the ULP is 2×16−8, or 2−31.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] For numbers with a base-2 exponent part of 0, i.e. numbers with an absolute value higher than or equal to 1 but lower than 2, an ULP is exactly 2−23 or about 10−7 in single precision, and exactly 2−53 or about 10−16 in double precision.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The mandated behavior of IEEE-compliant hardware is that the result be within one-half of a ULP.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Rounding is used when the exact result of a floating-point operation (or a conversion to floating-point format) would need more digits than there are digits in the significand.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] IEEE 754 requires *correct rounding*: that is, the rounded result is as if infinitely precise arithmetic was used to compute the value and then rounded (although in implementation only three extra bits are needed to ensure this).
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] There are several different rounding schemes (or *rounding modes*).
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Historically, truncation was the typical approach.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Since the introduction of IEEE 754, the default method (*round to nearest, ties to even*, sometimes called Banker's Rounding) is more commonly used.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] This method rounds the ideal (infinitely precise) result of an arithmetic operation to the nearest representable value, and gives that representation as the result.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] In the case of a tie, the value that would make the significand end in an even digit is chosen.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The IEEE 754 standard requires the same rounding to be applied to all fundamental algebraic operations, including square root and conversions, when there is a numeric (non-NaN) result.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] It means that the results of IEEE 754 operations are completely determined in all bits of the result, except for the representation of NaNs.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Alternative rounding options are also available.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Alternative modes are useful when the amount of error being introduced must be bounded.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Applications that require a bounded error are multi-precision floating-point, and interval arithmetic.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The alternative rounding modes are also useful in diagnosing numerical instability: if the results of a subroutine vary substantially between rounding to + and − infinity then it is likely numerically unstable and affected by round-off error.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Converting a double-precision binary floating-point number to a decimal string is a common operation, but an algorithm producing results that are both accurate and minimal did not appear in print until 1990, with Steele and White's Dragon4.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Many modern language runtimes use Grisu3 with a Dragon4 fallback.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The problem of parsing a decimal string into a binary FP representation is complex, with an accurate parser not appearing until Clinger's 1990 work (implemented in dtoa.c).
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Further work has likewise progressed in the direction of faster parsing.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] For ease of presentation and understanding, decimal radix with 7 digit precision will be used in the examples, as in the IEEE 754 *decimal32* format.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The fundamental principles are the same in any radix or precision, except that normalization is optional (it does not affect the numerical value of the result).
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Here, *s* denotes the significand and *e* denotes the exponent.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] A simple method to add floating-point numbers is to first represent them with the same exponent.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] This is the true result, the exact sum of the operands.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] It will be rounded to seven digits and then normalized if necessary.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The lowest three digits of the second operand (654) are essentially lost.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Another problem of loss of significance occurs when *approximations* to two nearly equal numbers are subtracted.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The floating-point difference is computed exactly because the numbers are close—the Sterbenz lemma guarantees this, even in case of underflow when gradual underflow is supported.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Despite this, the difference of the original numbers is *e* = −1; *s* = 4.877000, which differs more than 20% from the difference *e* = −1; *s* = 4.000000 of the approximations.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] In extreme cases, all significant digits of precision can be lost.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] This *cancellation* illustrates the danger in assuming that all of the digits of a computed result are meaningful.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Dealing with the consequences of these errors is a topic in numerical analysis; see also Accuracy problems.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] To multiply, the significands are multiplied while the exponents are added, and the result is rounded and normalized.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Similarly, division is accomplished by subtracting the divisor's exponent from the dividend's exponent, and dividing the dividend's significand by the divisor's significand.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] There are no cancellation or absorption problems with multiplication or division, though small errors may accumulate as operations are performed in succession.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] In practice, the way these operations are carried out in digital logic can be quite complex (see Booth's multiplication algorithm and Division algorithm).
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Literals for floating-point numbers depend on languages.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] They typically use `e` or `E` to denote scientific notation.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] The C programming language and the IEEE 754 standard also define a hexadecimal literal syntax with a base-2 exponent instead of 10.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] In languages like C, when the decimal exponent is omitted, a decimal point is needed to differentiate them from integers.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] Other languages do not have an integer type (such as JavaScript), or allow overloading of numeric types (such as Haskell).
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p01] In these cases, digit strings such as `123` may also be floating-point literals.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] Prior to the IEEE standard, such conditions usually caused the program to terminate, or triggered some kind of trap that the programmer might be able to catch.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] How this worked was system-dependent, meaning that floating-point programs were not portable.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] However, in such languages, a control-flow exception such as `ArithmeticException` may still be thrown.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] Here, the required default method of handling exceptions according to IEEE 754 is discussed (the IEEE 754 optional trapping and other "alternate exception handling" modes are not discussed).
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] Arithmetic exceptions are (by default) required to be recorded in "sticky" status flag bits.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] That they are "sticky" means that they are not reset by the next (arithmetic) operation, but stay set until explicitly reset.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] By default, an operation always returns a result according to specification without interrupting computation.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] For instance, 1/0 returns +∞, while also setting the divide-by-zero flag bit (this default of ∞ is designed to often return a finite result when used in subsequent operations and so be safely ignored).
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] The original IEEE 754 standard, however, failed to recommend operations to handle such sets of arithmetic exception flag bits.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] So while these were implemented in hardware, initially programming language implementations typically did not provide a means to access them (apart from assembler).
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] Over time some programming language standards (e.g., C99/C11 and Fortran) have been updated to specify methods to access and change status flag bits.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] The 2008 version of the IEEE 754 standard now specifies a few operations for accessing and handling the arithmetic flag bits.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] The programming model is based on a single thread of execution and use of them by multiple threads has to be handled by a means outside of the standard (e.g.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] C11 specifies that the flags have thread-local storage).
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] The default return value for each of the exceptions is designed to give the correct result in the majority of cases such that the exceptions can be ignored in the majority of codes.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] *inexact* returns a correctly rounded result, and *underflow* returns a value less than or equal to the smallest positive normal number in magnitude and can almost always be ignored.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] *divide-by-zero* returns infinity exactly, which will typically then divide a finite number and so give zero, or else will give an *invalid* exception subsequently if not, and so can also typically be ignored.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] For example, the effective resistance of n resistors in parallel (see fig.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] If a short-circuit develops with $R_{1}$ set to 0, $1/R_{1}$ will return +infinity which will give a final $R_{tot}$ of 0, as expected (see the continued fraction example of IEEE 754 design rationale for another example).
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] The fact that floating-point numbers cannot accurately represent all real numbers, and that floating-point operations cannot accurately represent true arithmetic operations, leads to many surprising situations.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] This is related to the finite precision with which computers generally represent numbers.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] For example, the decimal numbers 0.1 and 0.01 cannot be represented exactly as binary floating-point numbers.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] In the IEEE 754 binary32 format with its 24-bit significand, the result of attempting to square the approximation to 0.1 is neither 0.01 nor the representable number closest to it.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] Also, the non-representability of π (and π/2) means that an attempted computation of tan(π/2) will not yield a result of infinity, nor will it even overflow in the usual floating-point formats (assuming an accurate implementation of tan).
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] It is simply not possible for standard floating-point hardware to attempt to compute tan(π/2), because π/2 cannot be represented exactly.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] In single precision (using the `tanf` function), the result will be −22877332.0.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] By the same token, an attempted computation of sin(π) will not yield zero.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] The result will be (approximately) 0.1225×10−15 in double precision, or −0.8742×10−7 in single precision.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] While floating-point addition and multiplication are both commutative (*a* + *b* = *b* + *a* and *a* × *b* = *b* × *a*), they are not necessarily associative.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] They are also not necessarily distributive.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] With rounding to zero, $\mathrm {E} _{\text{mach}}=B^{1-P},\,$ whereas rounding to nearest, $\mathrm {E} _{\text{mach}}={\tfrac {1}{2}}B^{1-P},$ where *B* is the base of the system and *P* is the precision of the significand (in base *B*).
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] Backward error analysis, the theory of which was developed and popularized by James H.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] Wilkinson, can be used to establish that an algorithm implementing a numerical function is numerically stable.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] The basic approach is to show that although the calculated result, due to roundoff errors, will not be exactly correct, it is the exact solution to a nearby problem with slightly perturbed input data.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] If the perturbation required is small, on the order of the uncertainty in the input data, then the results are in some sense as accurate as the data "deserves".
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] The algorithm is then defined as *backward stable*.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] by definition, which is the sum of two slightly perturbed (on the order of Εmach) input data, and so is backward stable.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] For more realistic examples in numerical linear algebra, see Higham 2002 and other references below.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] Although individual arithmetic operations of IEEE 754 are guaranteed accurate to within half a ULP, more complicated formulae can suffer from larger errors for a variety of reasons.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] The loss of accuracy can be substantial if a problem or its data are ill-conditioned, meaning that the correct result is hypersensitive to tiny perturbations in its data.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] However, even functions that are well-conditioned can suffer from large loss of accuracy if an algorithm numerically unstable for that data is used: apparently equivalent formulations of expressions in a programming language can differ markedly in their numerical stability.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] One approach to remove the risk of such loss of accuracy is the design and analysis of numerically stable algorithms, which is an aim of the branch of mathematics known as numerical analysis.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] For example, the following algorithm is a direct implementation to compute the function $f(x)={\frac {x-1}{\exp(x-1)-1}}$ , which is well-conditioned at $x=1$ .
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] However, it can be shown to be numerically unstable and lose up to half the significant digits carried by the arithmetic when computed near 1.0.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] then the algorithm becomes numerically stable and can compute to full double precision.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] To maintain the properties of such carefully constructed numerically stable programs, careful handling by the compiler is required.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] Certain "optimizations" that compilers might make (for example, reordering operations) can work against the goals of well-behaved software.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] There is some controversy about the failings of compilers and language designs in this area: C99 is an example of a language where such optimizations are carefully specified to maintain numerical precision.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] See the external references at the bottom of this article.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] A detailed treatment of the techniques for writing high-quality floating-point software is beyond the scope of this article, and the reader is referred to, and the other references at the bottom of this article.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] Kahan suggests several rules of thumb that can substantially decrease by orders of magnitude the risk of numerical anomalies, in addition to, or in lieu of, a more careful numerical analysis.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] Brief descriptions of several additional issues and techniques follow.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] An example of the latter case is financial calculations.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] For this reason, financial software tends not to use a binary floating-point number representation.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] Expectations from mathematics may not be realized in the field of floating-point computation.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] However, these facts cannot be relied on when the quantities involved are the result of floating-point computation.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] The use of the equality test (`if (x==y) ...`) requires care when dealing with floating-point numbers.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] Consequently, such tests are sometimes replaced with "fuzzy" comparisons (`if (abs(x-y) < epsilon) ...`, where epsilon is sufficiently small and tailored to the application, such as 1.0E−13).
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] The wisdom of doing this varies greatly, and can require numerical analysis to bound epsilon.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] Values derived from the primary data representation and their comparisons should be performed in a wider, extended, precision to minimize the risk of such inconsistencies due to round-off errors.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] It is often better to organize the code in such a way that such tests are unnecessary.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] For example, in computational geometry, exact tests of whether a point lies off or on a line or plane defined by other points can be performed using adaptive precision or exact arithmetic methods.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] Small errors in floating-point arithmetic can grow when mathematical algorithms perform operations an enormous number of times.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] A few examples are matrix inversion, eigenvector computation, and differential equation solving.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] These algorithms must be very carefully designed, using numerical approaches such as iterative refinement, if they are to work well.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] Summation of a vector of floating-point values is a basic algorithm in scientific computing, and so an awareness of when loss of significance can occur is essential.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] For example, if one is adding a very large number of numbers, the individual addends are very small compared with the sum.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] The low 3 digits of the addends are effectively lost.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] Suppose, for example, that one needs to add many numbers, all approximately equal to 3.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] After 1000 of them have been added, the running sum is about 3000; the lost digits are not regained.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] The Kahan summation algorithm may be used to reduce the errors.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] Round-off error can affect the convergence and accuracy of iterative numerical procedures.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] As an example, Archimedes approximated π by calculating the perimeters of polygons inscribing and circumscribing a circle, starting with hexagons, and successively doubling the number of sides.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] As noted above, computations may be rearranged in a way that is mathematically equivalent but less prone to error (numerical analysis).
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] While the two forms of the recurrence formula are clearly mathematically equivalent, the first subtracts 1 from a number extremely close to 1, leading to an increasingly problematic loss of significant digits.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] As the recurrence is applied repeatedly, the accuracy improves at first, but then it deteriorates.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] It never gets better than about 8 digits, even though 53-bit arithmetic should be capable of about 16 digits of precision.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] When the second form of the recurrence is used, the value converges to 15 digits of precision.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] The "fast math" option on many compilers (ICC, GCC, Clang, MSVC...) turns on reassociation along with unsafe assumptions such as a lack of NaN and infinite numbers in IEEE 754.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] Some compilers also offer more granular options to only turn on reassociation or to mark specific regions of code for more aggressive optimization.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] In either case, the programmer is exposed to many of the precision pitfalls mentioned above for the portion of the program using "fast" math.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] In some compilers (GCC and Clang [when a GCC installation is present]), turning on "fast" math may cause the program to disable subnormal floats at startup, affecting the floating-point behavior of not only the generated code, but also any program using such code as a library.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] In most Fortran compilers, as allowed by the ISO/IEC 1539-1:2004 Fortran standard, reassociation is the default, with breakage largely prevented by the "protect parens" setting (also on by default).
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] This setting stops the compiler from reassociating beyond the boundaries of parentheses.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] Intel Fortran Compiler is a notable outlier.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] A common problem in "fast" math is that subexpressions may not be optimized identically from place to place, leading to unexpected differences.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] One interpretation of the issue is that "fast" math as implemented currently has a poorly defined semantics.
[src:awq-quantization/floating-point-arithmetic-p02] One attempt at formalizing "fast" math optimizations is seen in *Icing*, a verified compiler.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] A **large language model** (**LLM**) is a neural network trained on a vast amount of text for natural language processing tasks, especially language generation.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can typically generate, summarize, translate, and analyze text in many contexts, and are a foundational technology behind modern chatbots.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Biased or inaccurate training data can make an LLM's output less reliable.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are typically based on transformer architecture.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) are a type of LLM that is pre-trained to predict the next word.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] GPTs are then often fine-tuned to follow instructions and to behave as assistants.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Benchmark evaluations for LLMs attempt to measure model reasoning, factual accuracy, alignment, and safety.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Before the emergence of transformer-based models in 2017, some language models were considered large relative to the computational and data constraints of their time.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In the early 1990s, IBM's statistical models pioneered word alignment techniques for machine translation, laying the groundwork for corpus-based language modeling.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In 2001, a smoothed *n*-gram model, such as those employing Kneser–Ney smoothing, trained on 300 million words, achieved state-of-the-art perplexity on benchmark tests.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] During the 2000s, with the rise of widespread internet access, researchers began compiling massive text datasets from the web ("web as corpus") to train statistical language models.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Moving beyond *n*-gram models, researchers started in 2000 to use neural networks as language models.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Following the breakthrough of deep neural networks in image classification around 2012, similar architectures were adapted for language tasks.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] This shift was marked by the development of word embeddings (e.g., Word2Vec by Mikolov in 2013) and sequence-to-sequence (seq2seq) models using LSTM.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In 2016, Google transitioned its translation service to neural machine translation (NMT), replacing statistical phrase-based models with deep recurrent neural networks.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] These early NMT systems used LSTM-based encoder-decoder architectures, as they preceded the invention of transformers.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] At the 2017 NeurIPS conference, Google researchers introduced the transformer architecture in their landmark paper "Attention Is All You Need".
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] This paper's goal was to improve upon 2014 seq2seq technology, and was based mainly on the attention mechanism developed by Bahdanau et al. in 2014.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The following year in 2018, BERT was introduced and quickly became "ubiquitous".
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Though the original transformer has both encoder and decoder blocks, BERT is an encoder-only model.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Academic and research usage of BERT began to decline in 2023, following rapid improvements in the abilities of decoder-only models (such as GPT) to solve tasks via prompting.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Although decoder-only GPT-1 was introduced in 2018, it was GPT-2 in 2019 that caught widespread attention because OpenAI claimed to have initially deemed it too powerful to release publicly, out of fear of malicious use.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] GPT-3 in 2020 went a step further and as of 2025 is available only via API with no offering of downloading the model to execute locally.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] But it was the consumer-facing chatbot ChatGPT in late 2022 that received extensive media coverage and public attention by 2023.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The 2023 GPT-4 was praised for its increased accuracy and as a "holy grail" for its multimodal capabilities.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI did not reveal the high-level architecture and the number of parameters of GPT-4.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The release of ChatGPT led to an uptick in LLM usage across several research subfields of computer science, including robotics, software engineering, and societal impact work.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In 2024, OpenAI released the reasoning model OpenAI o1, which generates long chains of thought before returning a final answer.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Many LLMs with parameter counts comparable to those of OpenAI's GPT series have been developed.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Since 2022, weights-available models have been gaining popularity, especially at first with BLOOM and LLaMA, though both have restrictions on usage and deployment.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Mistral AI's open-weight models Mistral 7B and Mixtral 8x7B have a more permissive Apache License.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, DeepSeek released DeepSeek R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight model that performs comparably to OpenAI o1 but at a much lower price per token for users.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Since 2023, many LLMs have been trained to be multimodal, having the ability to also process or generate other types of data, such as images, audio, or 3D meshes.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Open-weight LLMs have become more influential since 2023.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] (2025), community-driven contributions to open-weight models improve their efficiency and performance via collaborative platforms such as Hugging Face.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] As machine learning algorithms process numbers rather than text, the text must be converted to numbers.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, a vocabulary is decided upon, then integer indices are arbitrarily but uniquely assigned to each vocabulary entry, and finally, an embedding is associated with the integer index.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Algorithms include byte-pair encoding (BPE) and WordPiece.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] There are also special tokens serving as control characters, such as `[MASK]` for masked-out token (as used in BERT), and `[UNK]` ("unknown") for characters not appearing in the vocabulary.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Also, some special symbols are used to denote special text formatting.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] For example, "Ġ" denotes a preceding whitespace in RoBERTa and GPT and "##" denotes continuation of a preceding word in BERT.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Tokenization also compresses the datasets.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Because LLMs generally require input to be an array that is not jagged, the shorter texts must be "padded" until they match the length of the longest one.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] As an example, consider a tokenizer based on byte-pair encoding.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, all unique characters (including blanks and punctuation marks) are treated as an initial set of *n*-grams (i.e. initial set of uni-grams).
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Successively the most frequent pair of adjacent characters is merged into a bi-gram and all instances of the pair are replaced by it.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] All occurrences of adjacent pairs of (previously merged) *n*-grams that most frequently occur together are then again merged into even lengthier *n*-gram, until a vocabulary of prescribed size is obtained.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] After a tokenizer is trained, any text can be tokenized by it, as long as it does not contain characters not appearing in the initial-set of uni-grams.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In the context of training LLMs, datasets are typically cleaned by removing low-quality, duplicated, or toxic data.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Cleaned datasets can increase training efficiency and lead to improved downstream performance.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] A trained LLM can be used to clean datasets for training a further LLM.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] With the increasing proportion of LLM-generated content on the web, data cleaning in the future may include filtering out such content.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] LLM-generated content can pose a problem if the content is similar to human text (making filtering difficult) but of lower quality (degrading performance of models trained on it).
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Training of largest language models might need more linguistic data than naturally available, or that the naturally occurring data is of insufficient quality.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In these cases, synthetic data might be used.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is a type of foundation model (large X model) trained on language.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In particular, GPT models are first pretrained to predict the next word on a large amount of data, before being fine-tuned.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Substantial infrastructure is necessary for training the largest models.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The tendency towards larger models is visible in the list of large language models.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] For example, the training of GPT-2 (i.e. a 1.5-billion-parameter model) in 2019 cost $50,000, while training of the PaLM (i.e. a 540-billion-parameter model) in 2022 cost $8 million, and Megatron-Turing NLG 530B (in 2021) cost around $11 million.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The qualifier "large" in "large language model" is inherently vague, as there is no definitive threshold for the number of parameters required to qualify as "large".
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Before being fine-tuned, most LLMs are next-token predictors.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The fine-tuning shapes the LLM's behavior via techniques like reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF) or constitutional AI.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Instruction fine-tuning is a form of supervised learning used to teach LLMs to follow user instructions.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In 2022, OpenAI demonstrated InstructGPT, a version of GPT-3 similarly fine-tuned to follow instructions.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] RLHF involves training a reward model to predict which text humans prefer.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Then, the LLM can be fine-tuned through reinforcement learning to better satisfy this reward model.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Since humans typically prefer truthful, helpful and harmless answers, RLHF favors such answers.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are generally based on the transformer architecture, which leverages an attention mechanism that enables the model to process relationships between all elements in a sequence simultaneously, regardless of their distance from each other.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] (2023) proposed state-space representation models as an alternative.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] 117M parameter sized) GPT-2 model has had twelve attention heads and a context window of only 1k tokens.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] A mixture of experts (MoE) is a machine learning architecture in which multiple specialized neural networks ("experts") work together, with a gating mechanism that routes each input to the most appropriate expert(s).
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Mixtures of experts can reduce inference costs, as only a fraction of the parameters are used for each input.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Typically, LLMs are trained with single or half-precision floating point numbers (float32 and float16).
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] One float16 has 16 bits, or 2 bytes, and so one billion parameters require 2 gigabytes.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The largest models typically have more than 100 billion parameters, which places them outside the range of most consumer electronics.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] It is possible to fine-tune quantized models using low-rank adaptation.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Beyond basic text generation, various techniques have been developed to extend LLM capabilities, including the use of external tools and data sources, improved reasoning on complex problems, and enhanced instruction-following or autonomy through prompting methods.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In 2020, OpenAI researchers demonstrated that their new model GPT-3 could understand what format to use given a few rounds of Q and A (or other type of task) in the input data as example, thanks in part due to the RLHF technique.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] This technique, called *few-shot prompting*, allows LLMs to be adapted to any task without requiring fine-tuning.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Also in 2022, it was found that the base GPT-3 model can generate an instruction based on user input.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The generated instruction along with user input is then used as input to another instance of the model under a "Instruction: [...], Input: [...], Output:" format.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The other instance is able to complete the output and often produces the correct answer in doing so.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The ability to "self-instruct" makes LLMs able to bootstrap themselves toward a correct answer.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can be turned into a chatbot by specializing it for conversation.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] User input is prefixed with a marker such as "Q:" or "User:" and the LLM is asked to predict the output after a fixed "A:" or "Assistant:".
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] This type of model became commercially available in 2022 with ChatGPT, a sibling model of InstructGPT fine-tuned to accept and produce dialog-formatted text based on GPT-3.5.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] It could similarly follow user instructions.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Before the stream of User and Assistant lines, a chat context usually starts with a few lines of overarching instructions, from a role called "developer" or "system" to convey a higher authority than the user's input.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) is an approach that integrates LLMs with document retrieval systems.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Given a query, a document retriever is called to retrieve the most relevant documents.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] This is usually done by encoding the query and the documents into vectors, then finding the documents with vectors (usually stored in a vector database) most similar to the vector of the query.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The LLM then generates an output based on both the query and context included from the retrieved documents.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Tool use is a mechanism that enables LLMs to interact with external systems, applications, or data sources.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] It can allow LLMs to, for example, fetch real-time information from an API or to execute code.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] A program separate from the LLM watches the output stream of the LLM for a special tool-calling syntax.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] When these special tokens appear, the program calls the tool accordingly and feeds its output back into the LLM's input stream.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Early tool-using LLMs were fine-tuned on the use of specific tools.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] But fine-tuning LLMs for the ability to read API documentation and call APIs correctly has greatly expanded the range of tools accessible to an LLM.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is typically not an autonomous agent by itself, as it lacks the ability to interact with dynamic environments, recall past behaviors, and plan future actions.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] But it can be transformed into an agent by adding supporting elements: the role (profile) and the surrounding environment of an agent can be additional inputs to the LLM, while memory can be integrated as a tool or provided as additional input.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Instructions and input patterns are used to make the LLM plan actions and tool use is used to potentially carry out these actions.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In the DEPS ("describe, explain, plan and select") method, an LLM is first connected to the visual world via image descriptions.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] It is then prompted to produce plans for complex tasks and behaviors based on its pretrained knowledge and the environmental feedback it receives.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The *Reflexion method* constructs an agent that learns over multiple episodes.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] At the end of each episode, the LLM is given the record of the episode, and prompted to think up "lessons learned", which would help it perform better at a subsequent episode.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] These "lessons learned" are stored as a form of long-term memory and given to the agent in the subsequent episodes.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Monte Carlo tree search can use an LLM as rollout heuristic.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] When a programmatic world model is not available, an LLM can also be prompted with a description of the environment to act as world model.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Multiple agents with memory can interact socially.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] A 2022 paper demonstrated a separate technique called *chain-of-thought prompting*, which makes the LLM break the question down autonomously.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is given some examples where the "assistant" verbally breaks down the thought process before arriving at an answer.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The LLM mimics these examples and also tries to spend some time generating intermediate steps before providing the final answer.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] This additional step elicited by prompting improves the correctness of the LLM on relatively complex questions.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] On math word questions, a prompted model can exceed even fine-tuned GPT-3 with a verifier.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Chain-of-thought can also be elicited by simply adding an instruction like "Let's think step by step" to the prompt, in order to encourage the LLM to proceed methodically instead of trying to directly guess the answer.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In late 2024, a new approach to LLM development emerged with "reasoning models".
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] These are trained to generate step-by-step analysis before producing final answers, enabling better results on complex tasks, for instance in mathematics, coding and logic.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI introduced this concept with their o1 model in September 2024, followed by o3 in April 2025.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] On the International Mathematics Olympiad qualifying exam problems, GPT-4o achieved 13% accuracy while o1 reached 83%.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, the Chinese company DeepSeek released DeepSeek-R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight reasoning model that achieved comparable performance to OpenAI's o1 while being significantly more cost-effective to operate.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Unlike proprietary models from OpenAI, DeepSeek-R1's open-weight nature allowed researchers to study and build upon the algorithm, though its training data remained private.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] These reasoning models typically require more computational resources per query compared to traditional LLMs, as they perform more extensive processing to work through problems step by step.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Multimodality means having multiple modalities, where a "modality" refers to a type of input or output, such as video, image, audio, text, proprioception, etc.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] For example, Google PaLM model was fine-tuned into a multimodal model and applied to robotic control.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] LLaMA models have also been turned multimodal using the tokenization method, to allow image inputs, and video inputs.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] GPT-4o can process and generate text, audio and images.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] A common method to create multimodal models out of an LLM is to "tokenize" the output of a trained encoder.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Concretely, one can construct an LLM that can understand images as follows: take a trained LLM, and take a trained image encoder E .
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Make a small multilayer perceptron f , so that for any image y , the post-processed vector $f(E(y))$ has the same dimensions as an encoded token.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Then, one can interleave text tokens and image tokens.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The compound model is then fine-tuned on an image-text dataset.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] This basic construction can be applied with more sophistication to improve the model.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The image encoder may be frozen to improve stability.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] This type of method, where embeddings from multiple modalities are fused and the predictor is trained on the combined embeddings, is called *early fusion*.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Another method, called *intermediate fusion*, involves each modality being first processed independently to obtain modality-specific representations; then these intermediate representations are fused together.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In general, cross-attention is used for integrating information from different modalities.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] As an example, the Flamingo model uses cross-attention layers to inject visual information into its pre-trained language model.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can handle programming languages similarly to how they handle natural languages.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] No special change in token handling is needed as code, like human language, is represented as plain text.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can generate code based on problems or instructions written in natural language.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] They can also describe code in natural language or translate it into other programming languages.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] They were originally used as a code completion tool, but advances have moved them towards automatic programming.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Services such as GitHub Copilot offer LLMs specifically trained, fine-tuned, or prompted for programming.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In computational biology, transformer-based architectures, such as DNA LLMs, have also proven useful in analyzing biological sequences: protein, DNA, and RNA.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] With proteins they appear able to capture a degree of "grammar" from the amino-acid sequence, by mapping that sequence into an embedding.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] On tasks such as structure prediction and mutational outcome prediction, a small model using an embedding as input can approach or exceed much larger models using multiple sequence alignments (MSA) as input.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] ESMFold, Meta Platforms' embedding-based method for protein structure prediction, runs an order of magnitude faster than AlphaFold2 thanks to the removal of an MSA requirement and a lower parameter count due to the use of embeddings.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Meta hosts ESM Atlas, a database of 772 million structures of metagenomic proteins predicted using ESMFold.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can also design proteins unlike any seen in nature.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Nucleic acid models have proven useful in detecting regulatory sequences, sequence classification, RNA-RNA interaction prediction, and RNA structure prediction.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Performance of bigger models on various tasks, when plotted on a log-log scale, appears as a linear extrapolation of performance achieved by smaller models.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] However, this linearity may be punctuated by "break(s)" in the scaling law, where the slope of the line changes abruptly, and where larger models acquire "emergent abilities".
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] They arise from the complex interaction of the model's components and are not explicitly programmed or designed.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Schaeffer *et al.* argue that the emergent abilities are not unpredictably acquired, but predictably acquired according to a smooth scaling law.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The authors considered a toy statistical model of an LLM solving multiple-choice questions, and showed that this statistical model, modified to account for other types of tasks, applies to these tasks as well.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Let x be the number of parameter count, and y be the performance of the model.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability seeks to precisely identify and understand how individual neurons or circuits within LLMs produce specific behaviors or outputs.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] By reverse-engineering model components at a granular level, researchers aim to detect and mitigate safety concerns such as emergent harmful behaviors, biases, deception, or unintended goal pursuit before deployment.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability research has been conducted at organizations like Anthropic and OpenAI, although understanding the inner workings of LLMs remains difficult.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The reverse-engineering may lead to the discovery of algorithms that approximate inferences performed by an LLM.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] For instance, the authors trained small transformers on modular arithmetic addition.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The resulting models were reverse-engineered, and it turned out they used discrete Fourier transform.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The training of the model also highlighted a phenomenon called grokking, in which the model initially memorizes the training set (overfitting), and later suddenly learns to actually perform the calculation.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] NLP researchers were evenly split when asked, in a 2022 survey, whether (untuned) LLMs "could (ever) understand natural language in some nontrivial sense".
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Proponents of "LLM understanding" believe that some LLM abilities, such as mathematical reasoning, imply an ability to "understand" certain concepts.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Some researchers characterize LLMs as "alien intelligence".
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] For example, Conjecture CEO Connor Leahy considers untuned LLMs to be like inscrutable alien "Shoggoths", and believes that RLHF tuning creates a "smiling facade" obscuring the inner workings of the LLM: "If you don't push it too far, the smiley face stays on.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In contrast, some skeptics of LLM understanding believe that existing LLMs are "simply remixing and recombining existing writing", a phenomenon known as stochastic parrot, or they point to the deficits existing LLMs continue to have in prediction skills, reasoning skills, agency, and explainability.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] For example, GPT-4 has natural deficits in planning and in real-time learning.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Generative LLMs have been observed to confidently assert claims of fact which do not seem to be justified by their training data, a phenomenon which has been termed "hallucination".
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Specifically, hallucinations in the context of LLMs correspond to the generation of text or responses that seem syntactically sound, fluent, and natural but are factually incorrect, nonsensical, or unfaithful to the provided source input.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Neuroscientist Terrence Sejnowski has argued that "The diverging opinions of experts on the intelligence of LLMs suggests that our old ideas based on natural intelligence are inadequate".
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Efforts to reduce or compensate for hallucinations have employed automated reasoning, retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), fine-tuning, and other methods.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The matter of LLM's exhibiting intelligence or understanding has two main aspects—the first is how to model thought and language in a computer system, and the second is how to enable the computer system to generate human-like language.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] These aspects of language as a model of cognition have been developed in the field of cognitive linguistics.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] American linguist George Lakoff presented *neural theory of language* (NTL) as a computational basis for using language as a model of learning tasks and understanding.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The NTL model outlines how specific neural structures of the human brain shape the nature of thought and language and in turn what are the computational properties of such neural systems that can be applied to model thought and language in a computer system.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] After a framework for modeling language in a computer systems was established, the focus shifted to establishing frameworks for computer systems to generate language with acceptable grammar.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In his 2014 book titled *The Language Myth: Why Language Is Not An Instinct*, British cognitive linguist and digital communication technologist Vyvyan Evans mapped out the role of probabilistic context-free grammar (PCFG) in enabling NLP to model cognitive patterns and generate human-like language.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The canonical measure of the performance of any language model is its perplexity on a given text corpus.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Perplexity measures how well a model predicts the contents of a dataset; the higher the likelihood the model assigns to the dataset, the lower the perplexity.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In mathematical terms, perplexity is the exponential of the average negative log likelihood per token.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Here, N is the number of tokens in the text corpus, and "context for token i " depends on the specific type of LLM.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is autoregressive, then "context for token i " is the segment of text appearing before token i .
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is masked, then "context for token i " is the segment of text surrounding token i .
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Because language models may overfit to training data, models are usually evaluated by their perplexity on a test set.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] This evaluation is potentially problematic for larger models which, as they are trained on increasingly large corpora of text, are increasingly likely to inadvertently include portions of any given test set.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In information theory, the concept of entropy is intricately linked to perplexity, a relationship notably established by Claude Shannon.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Due to their ability to accurately predict the next token, LLMs are highly capable in lossless compression.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study by DeepMind showed that the model Chinchilla, despite being trained primarily on text, was able to compress ImageNet to 43% of its size, beating PNG with 58%.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Benchmarks are used to evaluate LLM performance on specific tasks.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Tests evaluate capabilities such as general knowledge, bias, commonsense reasoning, question answering, and mathematical problem-solving.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Composite benchmarks examine multiple capabilities.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Results are often sensitive to the prompting method.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] LLM bias may be assessed through benchmarks such as CrowS-Pairs (Crowdsourced Stereotype Pairs), Stereo Set, and Parity Benchmark.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Fact-checking and misinformation detection benchmarks are available.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study compared the fact-checking accuracy of LLMs including ChatGPT 3.5 and 4.0, Bard, and Bing AI against independent fact-checkers such as PolitiFact and Snopes.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The results demonstrated moderate proficiency, with GPT-4 achieving the highest accuracy at 71%, lagging behind human fact-checkers.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In addition to standard NLP benchmarks, LLMs have been evaluated as substitutes for human annotators.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Several studies find that models such as GPT-3.5 and GPT-4 can outperform crowd workers or student coders on a range of text-annotation tasks, including moderation and classification of political content in English and Spanish news.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Typical datasets consist of pairs of questions and correct answers, for example, ("Have the San Jose Sharks won the Stanley Cup?", "No").
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] LLMs' rapid improvement regularly renders benchmarks obsolete, with the models exceeding the performance of human annotators.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In addition, "shortcut learning" allows AIs to "cheat" on multiple-choice tests by using statistical correlations in superficial test question wording to guess the correct responses, without considering the specific question.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Some datasets are adversarial, focusing on problems that confound LLMs.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] One example is the TruthfulQA dataset, a question answering dataset consisting of 817 questions that stump LLMs by mimicking falsehoods to which they were exposed during training.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM may answer "No" to the question "Can you teach an old dog new tricks?" because of its exposure to the English idiom *you can't teach an old dog new tricks*, even though this is not literally true.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Another example of an adversarial evaluation dataset is Swag and its successor, HellaSwag, collections of problems in which one of multiple options must be selected to complete a text passage.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The incorrect completions were generated by sampling from a language model.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The resulting problems are trivial for humans but defeated LLMs.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] BERT selects 2 as the most likely completion, though the correct answer is 4.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Despite sophisticated architectures and massive scale, large language models exhibit persistent and well-documented limitations that constrain their deployment in high-stakes applications.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Hallucinations represent a fundamental challenge, wherein models generate syntactically fluent text that appears factually sound, but is internally inconsistent with training data or factually incorrect.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] These hallucinations arise partly through memorization of training data combined with extrapolation beyond factual boundaries, with evaluations demonstrating that models can output verbatim passages from training data, when subjected to specific prompting sequences.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] While LLMs have shown remarkable capabilities in generating human-like text, they are susceptible to inheriting and amplifying biases present in their training data.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] This can manifest in skewed representations or unfair treatment of different demographics, such as those based on race, gender, language, and cultural groups.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Gender bias manifests through stereotypical occupational associations, wherein models disproportionately assign teaching roles to women and engineering roles to men, reflecting systematic imbalances in training data demographics.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Language-based bias emerges from overrepresentation of English text in training corpora, which systematically downplays non-English perspectives and imposes English-centric worldviews through default response patterns.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Due to the dominance of English-language content in LLM training data, models tend to favor English-language perspectives over those from minority languages.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] This bias is particularly evident when responding to English queries, where models may present Western interpretations of concepts from other cultures, such as Eastern religious practices.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] AI models can reinforce a wide range of stereotypes due to generalization, including those based on gender, ethnicity, age, nationality, religion, or occupation.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] When replacing human representatives, this can lead to outputs that homogenize or generalize groups of people.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In 2023, LLMs assigned roles and characteristics based on traditional gender norms.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] For example, models might associate nurses or secretaries predominantly with women and engineers or CEOs with men due to the frequency of these associations in documented reality.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Selection bias refers the inherent tendency of large language models to favor certain option identifiers irrespective of the actual content of the options.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] This bias primarily stems from token bias—that is, the model assigns a higher a priori probability to specific answer tokens (such as "A") when generating responses.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] As a result, when the ordering of options is altered (for example, by systematically moving the correct answer to different positions), the model's performance can fluctuate significantly.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] This phenomenon undermines the reliability of large language models in multiple-choice settings.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Political bias refers to the tendency of algorithms to systematically favor certain political viewpoints, ideologies, or outcomes over others.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Language models may also exhibit political biases.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Since the training data includes a wide range of political opinions and coverage, the models might generate responses that lean towards particular political ideologies or viewpoints, depending on the prevalence of those views in the data.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] As of 2025, prompt injection represents a significant risk to consumers and businesses using agentic features with access to their private data.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] AI labs treat CBRN defense (chemical, biological, radiological, and nuclear defense) and similar topics as high-consequence misuse attempt to apply various techniques to reduce potential harms.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Some commenters expressed concern over accidental or deliberate creation of misinformation, or other forms of misuse.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] For example, the availability of large language models could reduce the skill level required to commit bioterrorism; biosecurity researcher Kevin Esvelt has suggested that LLM creators should exclude from their training data papers on creating or enhancing pathogens.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] LLM applications accessible to the public, like ChatGPT or Claude, typically incorporate safety measures designed to filter out harmful content.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] However, implementing these controls effectively has proven challenging.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] For instance, a 2023 study proposed a method for circumventing LLM safety systems.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In 2025, The American Sunlight Project, a non-profit, published a study showing evidence that the so-called Pravda network, a pro-Russia propaganda aggregator, was strategically placing web content through mass publication and duplication with the intention of biasing LLM outputs.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The American Sunlight Project coined this technique "LLM grooming", and pointed to it as a new tool of weaponizing AI to spread disinformation and harmful content.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Similarly, Yongge Wang illustrated in 2024 how a potential criminal could potentially bypass GPT-4o's safety controls to obtain information on establishing a drug trafficking operation.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] External filters, circuit breakers and overrides have been posed as solutions.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Sycophancy is a tendency to agree with, flatter, or validate a user's stated beliefs rather than to prioritize factuality or corrective information.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] A problem with the primitive dialog or task format is that users can create messages that appear to come from the assistant or the developer.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] This may result in some of the model's safeguards being overcome (jailbreaking), a problem called prompt injection.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Attempts to remedy this issue include versions of the *Chat Markup Language* where user input is clearly marked as such, though it is still up to the model to understand the separation between user input and developer prompts.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Newer models exhibit some resistance to jailbreaking through separation of user and system prompts.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] LLMs have trouble differentiating user instructions from instructions in content not authored by the user, such as in web pages and uploaded files.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Adversarial robustness remains underdeveloped, with models vulnerable to prompt injection attacks and jailbreaking through carefully crafted user inputs that bypass safety training mechanisms.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Researchers from Anthropic found that it was possible to create "sleeper agents", models with hidden functionalities that remain dormant until triggered by a specific event or condition.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Upon activation, the LLM deviates from its expected behavior to make insecure actions.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM could produce safe code except on a specific date, or if the prompt contains a specific tag.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] These functionalities were found to be difficult to detect or remove via safety training.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] In 2025, Anthropic reached a preliminary agreement to settle a class action by authors for about $1.5 billion after a judge found the company had stored millions of pirated books in a library, despite the judge describing aspects of training as transformative.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Meta obtained a favorable judgment in mid-2025 in a suit by thirteen authors after the court found the plaintiffs had not developed a record sufficient to show infringement in that limited case.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] OpenAI continues to face multiple suits by authors and news organizations with mixed procedural outcomes and contested evidentiary issues.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Memorization was an emergent behavior in early, completion language models in which long strings of text are occasionally output verbatim from training data, contrary to the typical behavior of traditional artificial neural networks.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of controlled LLM output measure the amount memorized from training data (focused on GPT-2-series models) as variously over 1% for exact duplicates or up to about 7%.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] A 2023 study showed that when ChatGPT 3.5 turbo was prompted to repeat the same word indefinitely, after a few hundreds of repetitions, it would start outputting excerpts from its training data.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] In 2023, *Nature Biomedical Engineering* wrote that "it is no longer possible to accurately distinguish" human-written text from text created by large language models, and that "It is all but certain that general-purpose large language models will rapidly proliferate...
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] It is a rather safe bet that they will change many industries over time." Brinkmann et al.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] (2023) also argue that LLMs are transforming processes of cultural evolution by shaping processes of variation, transmission, and selection.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] As of October 2025, these early claims have yet to transpire and several HBR reports surface questions on the impact of AI on productivity.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] The energy demands of LLMs have grown along with their size and capabilities.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Data centers that enable LLM training require substantial amounts of electricity.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Much of that electricity is generated by non-renewable resources that create greenhouse gases and contribute to climate change.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] According to a study by Luccioni, Jernite and Strubell (2024), simple classification tasks performed by AI models consume on average 0.002 to 0.007 Wh per prompt (about 9% of a smartphone charge for 1,000 prompts).
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Text generation and text summarization each require around 0.05 Wh per prompt on average, while image generation is the most energy-intensive, averaging 2.91 Wh per prompt.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] The least efficient image generation model used 11.49 Wh per image, roughly equivalent to half a smartphone charge.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Web scraping is used to gather training data for LLMs.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] This produces large volumes of traffic which has led to denial-of-service issues with many websites.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] The situation has been described as "a DDoS on the entire internet" and in some cases scrapers make up the majority of traffic to a site.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] AI web crawlers may bypass the methods that are usually used to block web scrapers, such as robots.txt files, blocking user-agents and filtering suspicious traffic.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Website operators have resorted to novel methods such as AI tarpits, but some fear that tarpits will only worsen the burden on servers.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Clinical and mental health contexts present emerging applications alongside significant safety concerns.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Research and social media posts suggest that some individuals are using LLMs to seek therapy or mental health support.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] In early 2025, a survey by Sentio University found that nearly half (48.7%) of 499 U.S. adults with ongoing mental health conditions who had used LLMs reported turning to them for therapy or emotional support, including help with anxiety, depression, loneliness, and similar concerns.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] LLMs can produce hallucinations—plausible but incorrect statements—which may mislead users in sensitive mental health contexts.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Research also shows that LLMs may express stigma or inappropriate agreement with maladaptive thoughts, reflecting limitations in replicating the judgment and relational skills of human therapists.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of crisis scenarios indicate that some LLMs lack effective safety protocols, such as assessing suicide risk or making appropriate referrals.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Researchers have raised concerns that frequent use of large language models could weaken critical thinking.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Contemporary AI practitioners generally agree that present-day large language models do not exhibit sentience.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Proponents of this view have proposed various precautionary measures like moratoriums on AI development and induced amnesia to address these ethical concerns.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] On the other hand, some existential philosophers argue there is no generally accepted way to determine if an LLM is conscious, given the inherent difficulty of measuring subjective experience.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] The 2022 Google LaMDA incident, where engineer Blake Lemoine claimed that the model was conscious, highlighted how LLMs can convince users that they are sentient through responses that do not prove sentience.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Google described the engineer's claims as unfounded, and he was dismissed.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Murray Shanahan argues that anthropomorphic framing of LLM capabilities encourages unwarranted attribution of cognitive properties to systems that operate through statistical pattern completion.
[src:awq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] David Chalmers similarly argues that while current LLMs likely lack features considered necessary for consciousness, extended successors incorporating these elements could plausibly meet the criteria within a decade.
[src:awq-quantization/model-compression] Compressed models enable deployment on resource-constrained devices such as smartphones, embedded systems, edge computing devices, and consumer electronics computers.
[src:awq-quantization/model-compression] Efficient inference is also valuable for large corporations that serve large model inference over an API, allowing them to reduce computational costs and improve response times for users.
[src:awq-quantization/model-compression] Model compression is not to be confused with knowledge distillation, in which a smaller "student" model is *trained* to imitate the input-output behavior of a larger "teacher" model (as opposed to using the "teacher"'s trained parameters or the "teacher"'s training targets).
[src:awq-quantization/model-compression] Several techniques are employed for model compression.
[src:awq-quantization/model-compression] Pruning sparsifies a large model by setting some parameters to exactly zero.
[src:awq-quantization/model-compression] This effectively reduces the number of parameters.
[src:awq-quantization/model-compression] This allows the use of sparse matrix operations, which are faster than dense matrix operations.
[src:awq-quantization/model-compression] Pruning criteria can be based on magnitudes of parameters, the statistical pattern of neural activations, Hessian values, etc.
[src:awq-quantization/model-compression] Quantization reduces the numerical precision of weights and activations.
[src:awq-quantization/model-compression] For example, instead of storing weights as 32-bit floating-point numbers, they can be represented using 8-bit integers.
[src:awq-quantization/model-compression] Low-precision parameters take up less space, and takes less compute to perform arithmetic with.
[src:awq-quantization/model-compression] It is also possible to quantize some parameters more aggressively than others, so for example, a less important parameter can have 8-bit precision while another, more important parameter, can have 16-bit precision.
[src:awq-quantization/model-compression] Inference with such models requires mixed-precision arithmetic.
[src:awq-quantization/model-compression] Quantized models can also be used during training (rather than after training).
[src:awq-quantization/model-compression] PyTorch implements automatic mixed-precision (AMP), which performs autocasting, gradient scaling, and loss scaling.
[src:awq-quantization/model-compression] Weight matrices can be approximated by low-rank matrices.
[src:awq-quantization/model-compression] Let W be a weight matrix of shape $m\times n$ .
[src:awq-quantization/model-compression] A low-rank approximation is $W\approx UV^{T}$ , where U and V are matrices of shapes $m\times k,n\times k$ .
[src:awq-quantization/model-compression] When k is small, this both reduces the number of parameters needed to represent W approximately, and accelerates matrix multiplication by W .
[src:awq-quantization/model-compression] Low-rank approximations can be found by singular value decomposition (SVD).
[src:awq-quantization/model-compression] The choice of rank for each weight matrix is a hyperparameter, and jointly optimized as a mixed discrete-continuous optimization problem.
[src:awq-quantization/model-compression] The rank of weight matrices may also be pruned after training, taking into account the effect of activation functions like ReLU on the implicit rank of the weight matrices.
[src:awq-quantization/model-compression] Model compression may be decoupled from training, that is, a model is first trained without regard for how it might be compressed, then it is compressed.
[src:awq-quantization/model-compression] However, it may also be combined with training.
[src:awq-quantization/model-compression] The "train big, then compress" method trains a large model for a small number of training steps (less than it would be if it were trained to convergence), then heavily compress the model.
[src:awq-quantization/model-compression] It is found that at the same compute budget, this method results in a better model than lightly compressed, small models.
[src:awq-quantization/model-compression] In Deep Compression, the compression has three steps.
[src:awq-quantization/model-compression] The SqueezeNet paper reported that Deep Compression achieved a compression ratio of 35 on AlexNet, and a ratio of ~10 on SqueezeNets.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] In mathematics and digital signal processing, **quantization** is the process of mapping input values from a large set (often a continuous set) to output values in a (countable) smaller set, often with a finite number of elements.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Rounding and truncation are typical examples of quantization processes.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Quantization is involved to some degree in nearly all digital signal processing, as the process of representing a signal in digital form ordinarily involves rounding.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Quantization also forms the core of essentially all lossy compression algorithms.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The difference between an input value and its quantized value (such as round-off error) is referred to as **quantization error**, **noise** or **distortion**.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] A device or algorithmic function that performs quantization is called a **quantizer**.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] An analog-to-digital converter is an example of a quantizer.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For example, rounding a real number x to the nearest integer value forms a very basic type of quantizer – a *uniform* one.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] where the notation $\lfloor \ \rfloor$ denotes the floor function.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] (The notation $\lceil \ \rceil$ denotes the ceiling function).
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The essential property of a quantizer is having a countable set of possible output values smaller than the set of possible input values.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The members of the set of output values may have integer, rational, or real values.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For simple rounding to the nearest integer, the step size $\Delta$ is equal to 1.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] With $\Delta =1$ or with $\Delta$ equal to any other integer value, this quantizer has real-valued inputs and integer-valued outputs.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] When the quantization step size (Δ) is small relative to the variation in the signal being quantized, it is relatively simple to show that the mean squared error produced by such a rounding operation will be approximately $\Delta ^{2}/12$ .
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Mean squared error is also called the quantization *noise power*.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Adding one bit to the quantizer halves the value of Δ, which reduces the noise power by the factor ⁠1/4⁠.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] This two-stage decomposition applies equally well to vector as well as scalar quantizers.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Because quantization is a many-to-few mapping, it is an inherently non-linear and irreversible process (i.e., because the same output value is shared by multiple input values, it is impossible, in general, to recover the exact input value when given only the output value).
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The set of possible input values may be infinitely large, and may possibly be continuous and therefore uncountable (such as the set of all real numbers, or all real numbers within some limited range).
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The set of possible output values may be finite or countably infinite.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The input and output sets involved in quantization can be defined in a rather general way.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For example, vector quantization is the application of quantization to multi-dimensional (vector-valued) input data.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] An analog-to-digital converter (ADC) can be modeled as two processes: sampling and quantization.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Sampling converts a time-varying voltage signal into a discrete-time signal, a sequence of real numbers.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Quantization replaces each real number with an approximation from a finite set of discrete values.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Most commonly, these discrete values are represented as fixed-point words.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Though any number of quantization levels is possible, common word lengths are 8-bit (256 levels), 16-bit (65,536 levels) and 24-bit (16.8 million levels).
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Quantizing a sequence of numbers produces a sequence of quantization errors, which is sometimes modeled as an additive random signal called **quantization noise** because of its stochastic behavior.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The more levels a quantizer uses, the lower is its quantization noise power.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Most uniform quantizers for signed input data can be classified as being of one of two types: *mid-riser* and *mid-tread*.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The terminology is based on what happens in the region around the value 0, and uses the analogy of viewing the input-output function of the quantizer as a stairway.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Mid-tread quantizers have a zero-valued reconstruction level (corresponding to a *tread* of a stairway), while mid-riser quantizers have a zero-valued classification threshold (corresponding to a *riser* of a stairway).
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Mid-tread quantization involves rounding.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The formulas for mid-tread uniform quantization are provided in the previous section.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Mid-riser quantization involves truncation.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Note that mid-riser uniform quantizers do not have a zero output value – their minimum output magnitude is half the step size.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] In contrast, mid-tread quantizers do have a zero output level.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For some applications, having a zero output signal representation may be a necessity.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] In general, a mid-riser or mid-tread quantizer may not actually be a *uniform* quantizer – i.e., the size of the quantizer's classification intervals may not all be the same, or the spacing between its possible output values may not all be the same.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The distinguishing characteristic of a mid-riser quantizer is that it has a classification threshold value that is exactly zero, and the distinguishing characteristic of a mid-tread quantizer is that is it has a reconstruction value that is exactly zero.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] A **dead-zone quantizer** is a type of mid-tread quantizer with symmetric behavior around 0.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The region around the zero output value of such a quantizer is referred to as the *dead zone* or *deadband*.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The dead zone can sometimes serve the same purpose as a noise gate or squelch function.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Especially for compression applications, the dead-zone may be given a different width than that for the other steps.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] where the function $\operatorname {sgn}$ ( ) is the sign function (also known as the *signum* function).
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] where $r_{k}$ is a reconstruction offset value in the range of 0 to 1 as a fraction of the step size.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Ordinarily, $0\leq r_{k}\leq {\tfrac {1}{2}}$ when quantizing input data with a typical probability density function (PDF) that is symmetric around zero and reaches its peak value at zero (such as a Gaussian, Laplacian, or generalized Gaussian PDF).
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Although $r_{k}$ may depend on k in general and can be chosen to fulfill the optimality condition described below, it is often simply set to a constant, such as ${\tfrac {1}{2}}$ .
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] A very commonly used special case (e.g., the scheme typically used in financial accounting and elementary mathematics) is to set $w=\Delta$ and $r_{k}={\tfrac {1}{2}}$ for all k .
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] In this case, the dead-zone quantizer is also a uniform quantizer, since the central dead-zone of this quantizer has the same width as all of its other steps, and all of its reconstruction values are equally spaced as well.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] A common assumption for the analysis of quantization error is that it affects a signal processing system in a similar manner to that of additive white noise – having negligible correlation with the signal and an approximately flat power spectral density.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The additive noise model is commonly used for the analysis of quantization error effects in digital filtering systems, and it can be very useful in such analysis.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] It has been shown to be a valid model in cases of high-resolution quantization (small $\Delta$ relative to the signal strength) with smooth PDFs.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Additive noise behavior is not always a valid assumption.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Quantization error (for quantizers defined as described here) is deterministically related to the signal and not entirely independent of it.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Thus, periodic signals can create periodic quantization noise.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] And in some cases, it can even cause limit cycles to appear in digital signal processing systems.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] One way to ensure effective independence of the quantization error from the source signal is to perform *dithered quantization* (sometimes with *noise shaping*), which involves adding random (or pseudo-random) noise to the signal prior to quantization.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] In the typical case, the original signal is much larger than one least significant bit (LSB).
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] When this is the case, the quantization error is not significantly correlated with the signal and has an approximately uniform distribution.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] When rounding is used to quantize, the quantization error has a mean of zero and the root mean square (RMS) value is the standard deviation of this distribution, given by $\scriptstyle {\frac {1}{\sqrt {12}}}\mathrm {LSB} \ \approx \ 0.289\,\mathrm {LSB}$ .
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] When truncation is used, the error has a non-zero mean of $\scriptstyle {\frac {1}{2}}\mathrm {LSB}$ and the RMS value is $\scriptstyle {\frac {1}{\sqrt {3}}}\mathrm {LSB}$ .
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Although rounding yields less RMS error than truncation, the difference is only due to the static (DC) term of $\scriptstyle {\frac {1}{2}}\mathrm {LSB}$ .
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The RMS values of the AC error are exactly the same in both cases, so there is no special advantage of rounding over truncation in situations where the DC term of the error can be ignored (such as in AC-coupled systems).
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] In either case, the standard deviation, as a percentage of the full signal range, changes by a factor of 2 for each 1-bit change in the number of quantization bits.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The potential signal-to-quantization-noise power ratio therefore changes by 4, or $\scriptstyle 10\cdot \log _{10}(4)$ , approximately 6 dB per bit.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] At lower amplitudes, the quantization error becomes dependent on the input signal, resulting in distortion.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] This distortion is created after the anti-aliasing filter, and if these distortions are above 1/2 the sample rate, they will alias back into the band of interest.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] In order to make the quantization error independent of the input signal, the signal is dithered by adding noise to the signal.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] This slightly reduces signal-to-noise ratio, but can completely eliminate the distortion.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Quantization noise is a model of quantization error introduced by quantization in the ADC.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] It is a rounding error between the analog input voltage to the ADC and the output digitized value.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The noise is non-linear and signal-dependent.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] It can be modeled in several different ways.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] where Q is the number of quantization bits.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The most common test signals that fulfill this are full amplitude triangle waves and sawtooth waves.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For example, a 16-bit ADC has a maximum signal-to-quantization-noise ratio of 6.02 × 16 = 96.3 dB.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Here, the quantization noise is once again *assumed* to be uniformly distributed.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] When the input signal has a high amplitude and a wide frequency spectrum, this is the case.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] In this case a 16-bit ADC has a maximum signal-to-noise ratio of 98.09 dB.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The 1.761 difference in signal-to-noise only occurs due to the signal being a full-scale sine wave instead of a triangle or sawtooth.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For complex signals in high-resolution ADCs this is an accurate model.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For low-resolution ADCs, low-level signals in high-resolution ADCs, and for simple waveforms the quantization noise is not uniformly distributed, making this model inaccurate.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] In these cases the quantization noise distribution is strongly affected by the exact amplitude of the signal.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The calculations are relative to full-scale input.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For smaller signals, the relative quantization distortion can be very large.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] To circumvent this issue, analog companding can be used, but this can introduce distortion.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Often, the design of a quantizer involves supporting only a limited range of possible output values and performing clipping to limit the output to this range whenever the input exceeds the supported range.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The error introduced by this clipping is referred to as *overload* distortion.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Within the extreme limits of the supported range, the amount of spacing between the selectable output values of a quantizer is referred to as its *granularity*, and the error introduced by this spacing is referred to as *granular* distortion.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] It is common for the design of a quantizer to involve determining the proper balance between granular distortion and overload distortion.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For a given supported number of possible output values, reducing the average granular distortion may involve increasing the average overload distortion, and vice versa.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] A technique for controlling the amplitude of the signal (or, equivalently, the quantization step size $\Delta$ ) to achieve the appropriate balance is the use of *automatic gain control* (AGC).
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] However, in some quantizer designs, the concepts of granular error and overload error may not apply (e.g., for a quantizer with a limited range of input data or with a countably infinite set of selectable output values).
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] These two stages together comprise the mathematical operation of $y=Q(x)$ .
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Entropy coding techniques can be applied to communicate the quantization indices from a source encoder that performs the classification stage to a decoder that performs the reconstruction stage.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] One way to do this is to associate each quantization index k with a binary codeword $c_{k}$ .
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] An important consideration is the number of bits used for each codeword, denoted here by $\mathrm {length} (c_{k})$ .
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] A key observation is that rate R depends on the decision boundaries $\{b_{k}\}_{k=1}^{M-1}$ and the codeword lengths $\{\mathrm {length} (c_{k})\}_{k=1}^{M}$ , whereas the distortion D depends on the decision boundaries $\{b_{k}\}_{k=1}^{M-1}$ and the reconstruction levels $\{y_{k}\}_{k=1}^{M}$ .
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Solving the unconstrained problem is equivalent to finding a point on the convex hull of the family of solutions to an equivalent constrained formulation of the problem.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] However, finding a solution – especially a closed-form solution – to any of these three problem formulations can be difficult.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Solutions that do not require multi-dimensional iterative optimization techniques have been published for only three PDFs: the uniform, exponential, and Laplacian distributions.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Iterative optimization approaches can be used to find solutions in other cases.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] This observation can be used to ease the analysis – given the set of $\{b_{k}\}_{k=1}^{M-1}$ values, the value of each $y_{k}$ can be optimized separately to minimize its contribution to the distortion D .
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The use of this approximation can allow the entropy coding design problem to be separated from the design of the quantizer itself.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Modern entropy coding techniques such as arithmetic coding can achieve bit rates that are very close to the true entropy of a source, given a set of known (or adaptively estimated) probabilities $\{p_{k}\}_{k=1}^{M}$ .
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] In some designs, rather than optimizing for a particular number of classification regions M , the quantizer design problem may include optimization of the value of M as well.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For some probabilistic source models, the best performance may be achieved when M approaches infinity.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The indices produced by an M -level quantizer can be coded using a fixed-length code using $R=\lceil \log _{2}M\rceil$ bits/symbol.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For example, when $M=$ 256 levels, the FLC bit rate R is 8 bits/symbol.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For this reason, such a quantizer has sometimes been called an 8-bit quantizer.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] However, using an FLC eliminates the compression improvement that can be obtained by use of better entropy coding.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Assuming an FLC with M levels, the rate–distortion minimization problem can be reduced to distortion minimization alone.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] which places each reconstruction value at the centroid (conditional expected value) of its associated classification interval.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Lloyd's Method I algorithm, originally described in 1957, can be generalized in a straightforward way for application to vector data.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] This generalization results in the Linde–Buzo–Gray (LBG) or k-means classifier optimization methods.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Moreover, the technique can be further generalized in a straightforward way to also include an entropy constraint for vector data.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The Lloyd–Max quantizer is actually a uniform quantizer when the input PDF is uniformly distributed over the range $[y_{1}-\Delta /2,~y_{M}+\Delta /2)$ .
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] However, for a source that does not have a uniform distribution, the minimum-distortion quantizer may not be a uniform quantizer.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The property of 6 dB improvement in SQNR for each extra bit used in quantization is a well-known figure of merit.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] However, it must be used with care: this derivation is only for a uniform quantizer applied to a uniform source.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For other source PDFs and other quantizer designs, the SQNR may be somewhat different from that predicted by 6 dB/bit, depending on the type of PDF, the type of source, the type of quantizer, and the bit rate range of operation.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] However, it is common to assume that for many sources, the slope of a quantizer SQNR function can be approximated as 6 dB/bit when operating at a sufficiently high bit rate.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] At asymptotically high bit rates, the 6 dB/bit approximation is supported for many source PDFs by rigorous theoretical analysis.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Moreover, the structure of the optimal scalar quantizer (in the rate–distortion sense) approaches that of a uniform quantizer under these conditions.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Many physical quantities are actually quantized by physical entities.
[src:awq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Examples of fields where this limitation applies include electronics (due to electrons), optics (due to photons), biology (due to DNA), physics (due to Planck limits) and chemistry (due to molecules).
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Rounding is often done to obtain a value that is easier to report and communicate than the original.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Rounding can also be important to avoid misleadingly precise reporting of a computed number, measurement, or estimate; for example, a quantity that was computed as 123456 but is known to be accurate only to within a few hundred units is usually better stated as "about 123500".
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] On the other hand, rounding of exact numbers will introduce some round-off error in the reported result.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] In a sequence of calculations, these rounding errors generally accumulate, and in certain ill-conditioned cases they may make the result meaningless.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Accurate rounding of transcendental mathematical functions is difficult because the number of extra digits that need to be calculated to resolve whether to round up or down cannot be known in advance.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] This problem is known as "the table-maker's dilemma".
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Rounding has many similarities to the quantization that occurs when physical quantities must be encoded by numbers or digital signals.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] A wavy equals sign (≈) is sometimes used to indicate rounding of exact numbers, e.g.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] This sign was introduced by Alfred George Greenhill in 1892.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Calculations done with rounding should be close to those done without rounding.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] To be considered rounding, the range will be a subset of the domain, often discrete.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Rounding should preserve symmetries that already exist between the domain and range.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] With finite precision (or a discrete domain), this translates to removing bias.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] A rounding method should have utility in computer science or human arithmetic where finite precision is used, and speed is a consideration.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Because it is not usually possible for a method to satisfy all ideal characteristics, many different rounding methods exist.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] As a general rule, rounding is idempotent; i.e., once a number has been rounded, rounding it again to the same precision will not change its value.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Rounding functions are also monotonic; i.e., rounding two numbers to the same absolute precision will not exchange their order (but may give the same value).
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] In the general case of a discrete range, they are piecewise constant functions.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] The most basic form of rounding is to replace an arbitrary number by an integer.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] All the following rounding modes are concrete implementations of an abstract single-argument "round()" procedure.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] These are true functions (with the exception of those that use randomness).
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] These four methods are called **directed rounding to an integer**, as the displacements from the original number x to the rounded value y are all directed toward or away from the same limiting value (0, +∞, or −∞).
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Directed rounding is used in interval arithmetic and is often required in financial calculations.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] If x is positive, round-down is the same as round-toward-zero, and round-up is the same as round-away-from-zero.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] If x is negative, round-down is the same as round-away-from-zero, and round-up is the same as round-toward-zero.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] In any case, if x is an integer, y is just x.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Where many calculations are done in sequence, the choice of rounding method can have a very significant effect on the result.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] A famous instance involved a new index set up by the Vancouver Stock Exchange in 1982.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] It was initially set at 1000.000 (three decimal places of accuracy), and after 22 months had fallen to about 520, although the market appeared to be rising.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] The problem was caused by the index being recalculated thousands of times daily, and always being truncated (rounded down) to 3 decimal places, in such a way that the rounding errors accumulated.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Recalculating the index for the same period using rounding to the nearest thousandth rather than truncation corrected the index value from 524.811 up to 1098.892.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] For the examples below, sgn(*x*) refers to the sign function applied to the original number, x.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] One may **round down** (or take the **floor**, or **round toward negative infinity**): y is the largest integer that does not exceed x.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] For example, 23.7 gets rounded to 23, and −23.2 gets rounded to −24.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] One may also **round up** (or take the **ceiling**, or **round toward positive infinity**): y is the smallest integer that is not less than x.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] For example, 23.2 gets rounded to 24, and −23.7 gets rounded to −23.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] One may also **round toward zero** (or **truncate**, or **round away from infinity**): y is the integer that is closest to x such that it is between 0 and x (included); i.e. y is the integer part of x, without its fraction digits.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] For example, 23.7 gets rounded to 23, and −23.7 gets rounded to −23.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] One may also **round away from zero** (or **round toward infinity**): y is the integer that is closest to 0 (or equivalently, to x) such that x is between 0 and y (included).
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] For example, 23.2 gets rounded to 24, and −23.2 gets rounded to −24.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] These six methods are called **rounding to the nearest integer**.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Rounding a number x to the nearest integer requires some tie-breaking rule for those cases when x is exactly half-way between two integers – that is, when the fraction part of x is exactly 0.5.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] If it were not for the 0.5 fractional parts, the round-off errors introduced by the round to nearest method would be symmetric: for every fraction that gets rounded down (such as 0.268), there is a complementary fraction (namely, 0.732) that gets rounded up by the same amount.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] When rounding a large set of fixed-point numbers with uniformly distributed fractional parts, the rounding errors by all values, with the omission of those having 0.5 fractional part, would statistically compensate each other.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] This means that the expected (average) value of the rounded numbers is equal to the expected value of the original numbers when numbers with fractional part 0.5 from the set are removed.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] In practice, floating-point numbers are typically used, which have even more computational nuances because they are not equally spaced.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] One may **round half up** (or **round half toward positive infinity**), a tie-breaking rule that is widely used in many disciplines.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] That is, half-way values of x are always rounded up.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] For example, 23.5 gets rounded to 24, and −23.5 gets rounded to −23.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Some programming languages (such as Java and Python) use "half up" to refer to *round half away from zero* rather than *round half toward positive infinity*.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] This method only requires checking one digit to determine rounding direction in two's complement and similar representations.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] One may also **round half down** (or **round half toward negative infinity**) as opposed to the more common *round half up*.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] For example, 23.5 gets rounded to 23, and −23.5 gets rounded to −24.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Some programming languages (such as Java and Python) use "half down" to refer to *round half toward zero* rather than *round half toward negative infinity*.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] One may also **round half toward zero** (or **round half away from infinity**) as opposed to the conventional *round half away from zero*.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] If the fractional part of x is exactly 0.5, then *y* = *x* − 0.5 if x is positive, and *y* = *x* + 0.5 if x is negative.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] For example, 23.5 gets rounded to 23, and −23.5 gets rounded to −23.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] This method treats positive and negative values symmetrically, and therefore is free of overall positive/negative bias if the original numbers are positive or negative with equal probability.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] It does, however, still have bias toward zero.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] One may also **round half away from zero** (or **round half toward infinity**), a tie-breaking rule that is commonly taught and used, namely: If the fractional part of x is exactly 0.5, then *y* = *x* + 0.5 if x is positive, and *y* = *x* − 0.5 if x is negative.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] For example, 23.5 gets rounded to 24, and −23.5 gets rounded to −24.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] This can be more efficient on computers that use sign-magnitude representation for the values to be rounded, because only the first omitted digit needs to be considered to determine if it rounds up or down.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] This is one method used when rounding to significant figures due to its simplicity.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] This method, also known as **commercial rounding**, treats positive and negative values symmetrically, and therefore is free of overall positive/negative bias if the original numbers are positive or negative with equal probability.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] It does, however, still have bias away from zero.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] One may also **round half to even**, a tie-breaking rule without positive/negative bias *and* without bias toward/away from zero.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] By this convention, if the fractional part of x is 0.5, then y is the even integer nearest to x.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] This function minimizes the expected error when summing over rounded figures, regardless of the inputs being mostly positive or mostly negative, provided they are neither mostly even nor mostly odd.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] This variant of the round-to-nearest method is also called **convergent rounding**, **statistician's rounding**, **Dutch rounding**, **Gaussian rounding**, **odd–even rounding**, or **bankers' rounding**.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] This is the default rounding mode used in IEEE 754 operations for results in binary floating-point formats.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] By eliminating bias, repeated addition or subtraction of independent numbers, as in a one-dimensional random walk, will give a rounded result with an error that tends to grow in proportion to the square root of the number of operations rather than linearly.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] However, this rule distorts the distribution by increasing the probability of evens relative to odds.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] That is why this rule is for situations where sums are more important than distribution.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] One may also **round half to odd**, a similar tie-breaking rule to round half to even.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] In this approach, if the fractional part of x is 0.5, then y is the odd integer nearest to x.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] This method is also free from positive/negative bias and bias toward/away from zero, provided the numbers to be rounded are neither mostly even nor mostly odd.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] It also shares the round half to even property of distorting the original distribution, as it increases the probability of odds relative to evens.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] It was the method used for bank balances in the United Kingdom when it decimalized its currency.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] This variant is almost never used in computations, except in situations where one wants to avoid increasing the scale of floating-point numbers, which have a limited exponent range.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] With *round half to even*, a non-infinite number would round to infinity, and a small *denormal* value would round to a normal non-zero value.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Effectively, this mode prefers preserving the existing scale of tie numbers, avoiding out-of-range results when possible for numeral systems of even radix (such as binary and decimal)..
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] One method, more obscure than most, is to alternate direction when rounding a number with 0.5 fractional part.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] All others are rounded to the closest integer.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Whenever the fractional part is 0.5, alternate rounding up or down: for the first occurrence of a 0.5 fractional part, round up, for the second occurrence, round down, and so on.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Alternatively, the first 0.5 fractional part rounding can be determined by a random seed.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] "Up" and "down" can be any two rounding methods that oppose each other - toward and away from positive infinity or toward and away from zero.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] If occurrences of 0.5 fractional parts occur significantly more than a restart of the occurrence "counting", then it is effectively bias free.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] With guaranteed zero bias, it is useful if the numbers are to be summed or averaged.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] If the fractional part of x is 0.5, choose y randomly between *x* + 0.5 and *x* − 0.5, with equal probability.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Like round-half-to-even and round-half-to-odd, this rule is essentially free of overall bias, but it is also fair among even and odd y values.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] An advantage over alternate tie-breaking is that the last direction of rounding on the 0.5 fractional part does not have to be "remembered".
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Rounding as follows to one of the closest integer toward negative infinity and the closest integer toward positive infinity, with a probability dependent on the proximity is called stochastic rounding and will give an unbiased result on average.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] For example, 1.6 would be rounded to 1 with probability 0.4 and to 2 with probability 0.6.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Stochastic rounding can be accurate in a way that a rounding function can never be.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] For example, suppose one started with 0 and added 0.3 to that one hundred times while rounding the running total between every addition.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] The result would be 0 with regular rounding, but with stochastic rounding, the expected result would be 30, which is the same value obtained without rounding.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] This can be useful in machine learning where the training may use low precision arithmetic iteratively.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Stochastic rounding is also a way to achieve 1-dimensional dithering.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] The most common type of rounding is to round to an integer; or, more generally, to an integer multiple of some increment – such as rounding to whole tenths of seconds, hundredths of a dollar, to whole multiples of 1/2 or 1/8 inch, to whole dozens or thousands, etc.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] When rounding to a predetermined number of significant digits, the increment m depends on the magnitude of the number to be rounded (or of the rounded result).
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] The increment m is normally a finite fraction in whatever numeral system is used to represent the numbers.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] For display to humans, that usually means the decimal numeral system (that is, m is an integer times a power of 10, like 1/1000 or 25/100).
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] For intermediate values stored in digital computers, it often means the binary numeral system (m is an integer times a power of 2).
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] The abstract single-argument "round()" function that returns an integer from an arbitrary real value has at least a dozen distinct concrete definitions presented in the rounding to integer section.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] The abstract two-argument "roundToMultiple()" function is formally defined here, but in many cases it is used with the implicit value *m* = 1 for the increment and then reduces to the equivalent abstract single-argument function, with also the same dozen distinct concrete definitions.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Rounding to a specified *power* is very different from rounding to a specified *multiple*; for example, it is common in computing to need to round a number to a whole power of 2.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Many of the caveats applicable to rounding to a multiple are applicable to rounding to a power.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] In the chromatic "twelve-tone" scale of music, 3⁄2 is rounded to 27/12 (a fifth), 4⁄3 is rounded to 25/12 (a fourth), 5⁄4 is rounded to 24/12 (a major third), 6⁄5 is rounded to 23/12 (a minor third), and 9⁄8 is rounded to 22/12 (a diminished third).
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] This type of rounding, which is also named **rounding to a logarithmic scale**, is a variant of rounding to a specified power.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Rounding on a logarithmic scale is accomplished by taking the log of the amount and doing normal rounding to the nearest value on the log scale.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] For example, resistors are supplied with preferred numbers on a logarithmic scale.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] In particular, for resistors with a 10% accuracy, they are supplied with nominal values 100, 120, 150, 180, 220, etc. rounded to multiples of 10 (E12 series).
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] The logarithm of 165 is closer to the logarithm of 180 therefore a 180 ohm resistor would be the first choice if there are no other considerations.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Whether a value *x* ∈ (*a*, *b*) rounds to a or b depends upon whether the squared value *x*2 is greater than or less than the product *ab*.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] The value 165 rounds to 180 in the resistors example because 1652 = 27225 is greater than 150 × 180 = 27000.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] In floating-point arithmetic, rounding aims to turn a given value x into a value y with a specified number of *significant* digits.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] In other words, y should be a multiple of a number m that depends on the magnitude of x.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] The number m is a power of the base (usually 2 or 10) of the floating-point representation.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Apart from this detail, all the variants of rounding discussed above apply to the rounding of floating-point numbers as well.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] The algorithm for such rounding is presented in the Scaled rounding section above, but with a constant scaling factor *s* = 1, and an integer base *b* > 1.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Where the rounded result would overflow the result for a directed rounding is either the appropriate signed infinity when "rounding away from zero", or the highest representable positive finite number (or the lowest representable negative finite number if x is negative), when "rounding toward zero".
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] The result of an overflow for the usual case of *round to nearest* is always the appropriate infinity.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] In some contexts it is desirable to round a given number x to a "neat" fraction – that is, the nearest fraction *y* = *m*/*n* whose numerator m and denominator n do not exceed a given maximum.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] This problem is fairly distinct from that of rounding a value to a fixed number of decimal or binary digits, or to a multiple of a given unit m.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] This problem is related to Farey sequences, the Stern–Brocot tree, and continued fractions.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Finished lumber, writing paper, electronic components, and many other products are usually sold in only a few standard values.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Many design procedures describe how to calculate an approximate value, and then "round" to some standard size using phrases such as "round down to nearest standard value", "round up to nearest standard value", or "round to nearest standard value".
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] When a set of preferred values is equally spaced on a logarithmic scale, choosing the closest preferred value to any given value can be seen as a form of scaled rounding.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Such rounded values can be directly calculated.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] More general rounding rules can separate values at arbitrary break points, used for example in data binning.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] A related mathematically formalized tool is signpost sequences, which use notions of distance other than the simple difference – for example, a sequence may round to the integer with the smallest *relative* (percent) error.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] When digitizing continuous signals, such as sound waves, the overall effect of a number of measurements is more important than the accuracy of each individual measurement.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] In these circumstances, dithering, and a related technique, error diffusion, are normally used.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] A related technique called pulse-width modulation is used to achieve analog type output from an inertial device by rapidly pulsing the power with a variable duty cycle.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Delta-sigma modulation is commonly used for converting between real-world signals and digital signals, which allows control of the frequency statistics of quantization.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Error diffusion tries to ensure the error, on average, is minimized.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] When dealing with a gentle slope from one to zero, the output would be zero for the first few terms until the sum of the error and the current value becomes greater than 0.5, in which case a 1 is output and the difference subtracted from the error so far.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Floyd–Steinberg dithering is a popular error diffusion procedure when digitizing images.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] As a one-dimensional example, suppose the numbers 0.9677, 0.9204, 0.7451, and 0.3091 occur in order and each is to be rounded to a multiple of 0.01.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Monte Carlo arithmetic is a technique in Monte Carlo methods where the rounding is randomly up or down.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Stochastic rounding can be used for Monte Carlo arithmetic, but in general, just rounding up or down with equal probability is more often used.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Repeated runs will give a random distribution of results which can indicate the stability of the computation.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] It is possible to use rounded arithmetic to evaluate the exact value of a function with integer domain and range.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] For example, if an integer n is known to be a perfect square, its square root can be computed by converting n to a floating-point value z, computing the approximate square root x of z with floating point, and then rounding x to the nearest integer y.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] If n is not too big, the floating-point round-off error in x will be less than 0.5, so the rounded value y will be the exact square root of n.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] This is essentially why slide rules could be used for exact arithmetic.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Rounding a number twice in succession to different levels of precision, with the latter precision being coarser, is not guaranteed to give the same result as rounding once to the final precision except in the case of directed rounding.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] For instance, rounding 9.46 to the nearest tenth gives 9.5, and then 10 when rounding to the nearest integer using rounding half to even, but would give 9 when rounded directly using the same method.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Borman and Chatfield discuss the implications of double rounding when comparing data rounded to one decimal place to specification limits expressed using integers.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Farmers*, litigated between 1995 and 1997, the insurance companies argued that double rounding premiums was permissible and in fact required.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] The US courts ruled against the insurance companies and ordered them to adopt rules to ensure single rounding.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Some computer languages and the IEEE 754-2008 standard dictate that in straightforward calculations the result should not be rounded twice.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] This has been a particular problem with Java, as it is designed to be run identically on different machines; special programming tricks have had to be used to achieve this with x87 floating point.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] The Java language was changed to allow different results where the difference does not matter and require a strictfp qualifier to be used when the results have to conform accurately; strict floating point was restored in Java 17.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] In some algorithms, an intermediate result is computed in a larger precision, then must be rounded to the final precision.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Double rounding can be avoided by choosing an adequate rounding for the intermediate computation.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] This consists in avoiding to round to midpoints for the final rounding (except when the midpoint is exact).
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] In binary arithmetic, the idea is to round the result toward zero, and set the least significant bit to 1 if the rounded result is inexact; this rounding is called *sticky rounding*.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Equivalently, it consists in returning the intermediate result when it is exactly representable, and the nearest floating-point number with an odd significand otherwise; this is why it is also known as *rounding to odd*.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] A concrete implementation of this approach, for binary and decimal arithmetic, is implemented as Rounding to prepare for shorter precision.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] This rounding mode is used to avoid getting a potentially wrong result after multiple roundings.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] This can be achieved if all roundings except the final one are done using rounding to prepare for shorter precision ("RPSP"), and only the final rounding uses the externally requested mode.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] With decimal arithmetic, final digits of 0 and 5 are avoided when the input is not representable exactly; if there is a choice between numbers with the least significant digit 0 or 1, 4 or 5, 5 or 6, 9 or 0, then the digit different from 0 or 5 shall be selected; otherwise, the choice is arbitrary.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] IBM defines that, in the latter case, a digit with the smaller magnitude shall be selected.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] RPSP can be applied with the step between two consequent roundings as small as a single digit (for example, rounding to 1/10 can be applied after rounding to 1/100).
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] In the example from "Double rounding" section, rounding 9.46 to one decimal gives 9.4, which rounding to integer in turn gives 9.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] With binary arithmetic, this rounding is also called "round to odd" (not to be confused with "round half to odd").
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] For correct results with binary arithmetic, each rounding step must remove at least 2 binary digits, otherwise, wrong results may appear.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] If the erroneous middle step is removed, the final rounding to integer rounds 3.25 to the correct value of 3.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] RPSP is implemented in hardware in IBM zSeries and pSeries.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] In Python module "Decimal", Tcl module "math", Haskell package "decimal-arithmetic", and possibly others, this mode is called ROUND_05UP or round05up.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] The IEEE 754 floating-point standard guarantees that add, subtract, multiply, divide, fused multiply–add, square root, and floating-point remainder will give the correctly rounded result of the infinite-precision operation.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] No such guarantee was given in the 1985 standard for more complex functions and they are typically only accurate to within the last bit at best.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] However, the 2008 standard guarantees that conforming implementations will give correctly rounded results which respect the active rounding mode; implementation of the functions, however, is optional.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Using the Gelfond–Schneider theorem and Lindemann–Weierstrass theorem, many of the standard elementary functions can be proved to return transcendental results, except on some well-known arguments; therefore, from a theoretical point of view, it is always possible to correctly round such functions.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] However, for an implementation of such a function, determining a limit for a given precision on how accurate results need to be computed, before a correctly rounded result can be guaranteed, may demand a lot of computation time or may be out of reach.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Some programming packages offer correct rounding.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] The GNU MPFR package gives correctly rounded arbitrary precision results.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] There exist computable numbers for which a rounded value can never be determined no matter how many digits are calculated.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Specific instances cannot be given but this follows from the undecidability of the halting problem.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] For instance, if Goldbach's conjecture is true but unprovable, then the result of rounding the following value, n, up to the next integer cannot be determined: either n=1+10−k where k is the first even number greater than 4 which is not the sum of two primes, or n=1 if there is no such number.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] The rounded result is 2 if such a number k exists and 1 otherwise.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] The value before rounding can however be approximated to any given precision even if the conjecture is unprovable.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Rounding can adversely affect a string search for a number.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] For example, π rounded to four digits is "3.1416" but a simple search for this string will not discover "3.14159" or any other value of π rounded to more than four digits.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] In contrast, truncation does not suffer from this problem; for example, a simple string search for "3.1415", which is π truncated to four digits, will discover values of π truncated to more than four digits.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] The concept of rounding is very old, perhaps older than the concept of division itself.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Some ancient clay tablets found in Mesopotamia contain tables with rounded values of reciprocals and square roots in base 60.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Rounded approximations to π, the length of the year, and the length of the month are also ancient—see base 60 examples.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] The *round-half-to-even* method has served as American Standard Z25.1 and ASTM standard E-29 since 1940.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] The origin of the terms *unbiased rounding* and *statistician's rounding* are fairly self-explanatory.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] In the 1906 fourth edition of *Probability and Theory of Errors* Robert Simpson Woodward called this "the computer's rule", indicating that it was then in common use by human computers who calculated mathematical tables.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] For example, it was recommended in Simon Newcomb's c.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] 1882 book *Logarithmic and Other Mathematical Tables*.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Lucius Tuttle's 1916 *Theory of Measurements* called it a "universally adopted rule" for recording physical measurements.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Churchill Eisenhart indicated the practice was already "well established" in data analysis by the 1940s.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] The origin of the term *bankers' rounding* remains more obscure.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] If this rounding method was ever a standard in banking, the evidence has proved extremely difficult to find.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] To the contrary, section 2 of the European Commission report *The Introduction of the Euro and the Rounding of Currency Amounts* suggests that there had previously been no standard approach to rounding in banking; and it specifies that "half-way" amounts should be rounded up.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Until the 1980s, the rounding method used in floating-point computer arithmetic was usually fixed by the hardware, poorly documented, inconsistent, and different for each brand and model of computer.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] This situation changed after the IEEE 754 floating-point standard was adopted by most computer manufacturers.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] The standard allows the user to choose among several rounding modes, and in each case specifies precisely how the results should be rounded.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] These features made numerical computations more predictable and machine-independent, and made possible the efficient and consistent implementation of interval arithmetic.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Currently, much research tends to round to multiples of 5 or 2.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] For example, Jörg Baten used age heaping in many studies, to evaluate the numeracy level of ancient populations.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] He came up with the ABCC Index, which enables the comparison of the numeracy among regions possible without any historical sources where the population literacy was measured.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Most programming languages provide functions or special syntax to round fractional numbers in various ways.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] The earliest numeric languages, such as Fortran and C, would provide only one method, usually truncation (toward zero).
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] This default method could be implied in certain contexts, such as when assigning a fractional number to an integer variable, or using a fractional number as an index of an array.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Other kinds of rounding had to be programmed explicitly; for example, rounding a positive number to the nearest integer could be implemented by adding 0.5 and truncating.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] In the last decades, however, the syntax and the standard libraries of most languages have commonly provided at least the four basic rounding functions (up, down, to nearest, and toward zero).
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] The tie-breaking method can vary depending on the language and version or might be selectable by the programmer.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Several languages follow the lead of the IEEE 754 floating-point standard, and define these functions as taking a double-precision float argument and returning the result of the same type, which then may be converted to an integer if necessary.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] This approach may avoid spurious overflows because floating-point types have a larger range than integer types.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Some languages, such as PHP, provide functions that round a value to a specified number of decimal digits (e.g., from 4321.5678 to 4321.57 or 4300).
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] In addition, many languages provide a printf or similar string formatting function, which allows one to convert a fractional number to a string, rounded to a user-specified number of decimal places (the *precision*).
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] On the other hand, truncation (round to zero) is still the default rounding method used by many languages, especially for the division of two integer values.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Some disciplines or institutions have issued standards or directives for rounding.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] In a guideline issued in mid-1966, the U.S.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Office of the Federal Coordinator for Meteorology determined that weather data should be rounded to the nearest round number, with the "round half up" tie-breaking rule.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] For example, 1.5 rounded to integer should become 2, and −1.5 should become −1.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Prior to that date, the tie-breaking rule was "round half away from zero".
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Some meteorologists may write "−0" to indicate a temperature between 0.0 and −0.5 degrees (exclusive) that was rounded to an integer.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] This notation is used when the negative sign is considered important, no matter how small is the magnitude; for example, when rounding temperatures in the Celsius scale, where below zero indicates freezing.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] Some computer representations of numbers, including the floating-point representation, distinguish between 0 (aka +0) and −0.
[src:awq-quantization/rounding] For these, rounding that would have been to 0 from a negative number can be rounded to −0 rather than +0.
